# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: legacy-languages
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Ada was originally designed by a team led by French computer scientist Jean Ichbiah of Honeywell under contract to the United States Department of Defense (DoD) from 1977 to 1983 to supersede over 450 programming languages then used by the DoD.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Ada was named after Ada Lovelace (1815–1852), who has been credited as the first computer programmer.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Ada was originally designed for embedded and real-time systems.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Tucker Taft of Intermetrics between 1992 and 1995, improved support for systems, numerical, financial, and object-oriented programming (OOP).
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Features of Ada include strong typing, modular programming mechanisms (packages), run-time checking, parallel processing (tasks, synchronous message passing, protected objects, and nondeterministic select statements), exception handling, and generics.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Ada 95 added support for object-oriented programming, including dynamic dispatch.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] The syntax of Ada minimizes choices of ways to perform basic operations, and prefers English keywords (such as `or else` and `and then`) to symbols (such as `||` and `&&`).
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Ada uses the basic arithmetical operators `+`, `-`, `*`, and `/`, but avoids using other symbols.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Code blocks are delimited by words such as 'declare', 'begin', and 'end', where the 'end' (in most cases) is followed by the keyword of the block that it closes (e.g., `if` ...
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] In the case of conditional blocks this avoids a *dangling else* that could pair with the wrong nested 'if'-expression in other languages such as C or Java.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Ada is designed for developing very large software systems.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Ada packages can be compiled separately.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Ada package specifications (the package interface) can also be compiled separately without the implementation to check for consistency.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] This makes it possible to detect problems early during the design phase, before implementation starts.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] A large number of compile-time checks are supported to help avoid bugs that would not be detectable until run time in some other languages or would require explicit checks to be added to the source code.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] For example, the syntax requires explicitly named closing of blocks to prevent errors due to mismatched end tokens.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] The adherence to strong typing allows detecting many common software errors (wrong parameters, range violations, invalid references, mismatched types, etc.) either during compile time, or otherwise during run time.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] As concurrency is part of the language specification, the compiler can in some cases detect potential deadlocks.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Compilers also commonly check for misspelled identifiers, visibility of packages, redundant declarations, etc. and can provide warnings and useful suggestions on how to fix the error.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Ada also supports run-time checks to protect against access to unallocated memory, buffer overflow errors, range violations, off-by-one errors, array access errors, and other detectable bugs.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] These checks can be disabled in the interest of runtime efficiency, but can often be compiled efficiently.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] It also includes facilities to help program verification.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] For these reasons, Ada is sometimes used in critical systems, where any anomaly might lead to very serious consequences, e.g., accidental death, injury or severe financial loss.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Examples of systems where Ada is used include avionics, air traffic control, railways, banking, military and space technology.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Ada's dynamic memory management is high-level and type-safe.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Ada has no generic or untyped pointers, nor does it implicitly declare any pointer type.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Instead, all dynamic memory allocation and deallocation must occur via explicitly declared *access types*.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Each access type has an associated *storage pool* that handles the low-level details of memory management; the programmer can either use the default storage pool or define new ones (this is particularly relevant for non-uniform memory access).
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] It is even possible to declare several different access types that all designate the same type but use different storage pools.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Also, the language provides for *accessibility checks*, both at compile time and at run time, that ensures that an *access value* cannot outlive the type of the object it points to.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Though the semantics of the language allow automatic garbage collection of inaccessible objects, most implementations do not support it by default, as it would cause unpredictable behaviour in real-time systems.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Ada supports a limited form of region-based memory management, and in Ada, destroying a storage pool also destroys all the objects in the pool.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] A double dash (`--`), resembling an em dash, denotes comment text.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Comments stop at end of line; there is intentionally no way to make a comment span multiple lines, to prevent unclosed comments from accidentally voiding whole sections of source code.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Disabling a whole block of code therefore requires the prefixing of each line (or column) individually with `--`.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] While this clearly denotes disabled code by creating a column of repeated '--' down the page, it also renders the experimental dis/re-enablement of large blocks a more drawn-out process in editors without block commenting support.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] The semicolon (`;`) is a statement terminator, and the null or no-operation statement is `null;`.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] A single `;` without a statement to terminate is not allowed.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Unlike most ISO standards, the Ada language definition (known as the *Ada Reference Manual* or *ARM*, or sometimes the *Language Reference Manual* or *LRM*) is free content.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Thus, it is a common reference for Ada programmers, not only programmers implementing Ada compilers.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Apart from the reference manual, there is also an extensive rationale document which explains the language design and the use of various language constructs.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] This document is also widely used by programmers.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] When the language was revised, a new rationale document was written.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] One notable free software tool that is used by many Ada programmers to aid them in writing Ada source code is the GNAT Programming Studio, and GNAT which is part of the GNU Compiler Collection.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] In the 1970s the US Department of Defense (DoD) became concerned by the number of different programming languages being used for its embedded computer system projects, many of which were obsolete or hardware-dependent, and none of which supported safe modular programming.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] In 1975, a working group, the High Order Language Working Group (HOLWG), was formed with the intent to reduce this number by finding or creating a programming language generally suitable for the department's and the UK Ministry of Defence's requirements.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] After many iterations beginning with an original straw-man proposal the eventual programming language was named Ada.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] The total number of high-level programming languages in use for such projects fell from over 450 in 1983 to 37 by 1996.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] HOLWG crafted the **Steelman language requirements**, a series of documents stating the requirements they felt a programming language should satisfy.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Many existing languages were formally reviewed, but the team concluded in 1977 that no existing language met the specifications.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] The requirements were created by the United States Department of Defense in *The Department of Defense Common High Order Language program* in 1978.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] The predecessors of this document were called, in order, "Strawman", "Woodenman", "Tinman" and "Ironman".
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] The requirements focused on the needs of embedded computer applications, and emphasised reliability, maintainability, and efficiency.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Notably, they included exception handling facilities, run-time checking, and parallel computing.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] It was concluded that no existing language met these criteria to a sufficient extent, so a contest was called to create a language that would be closer to fulfilling them.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] The design that won this contest became the Ada programming language.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] The resulting language followed the Steelman requirements closely, though not exactly.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] In April 1978, after public scrutiny, the Red and Green proposals passed to the next phase.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] In May 1979, the Green proposal, designed by Jean Ichbiah at Honeywell, was chosen and given the name Ada—after Augusta Ada King, Countess of Lovelace, usually known as Ada Lovelace.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] This proposal was influenced by the language LIS that Ichbiah and his group had developed in the 1970s.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] The preliminary Ada reference manual was published in ACM SIGPLAN Notices in June 1979.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] The Military Standard reference manual was approved on December 10, 1980 (Ada Lovelace's birthday), and given the number MIL-STD-1815 in honor of Ada Lovelace's birth year.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] In 1981, Tony Hoare took advantage of his Turing Award speech to criticize Ada for being overly complex and hence unreliable, but subsequently seemed to recant in the foreword he wrote for an Ada textbook.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Ada attracted much attention from the programming community as a whole during its early days.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Its backers and others predicted that it might become a dominant language for general purpose programming and not only defense-related work.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Ichbiah publicly stated that within ten years, only two programming languages would remain: Ada and Lisp.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Early Ada compilers struggled to implement the large, complex language, and both compile-time and run-time performance tended to be slow and tools primitive.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Compiler vendors expended most of their efforts in passing the massive, language-conformance-testing, government-required Ada Compiler Validation Capability (ACVC) validation suite that was required in another novel feature of the Ada language effort.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] The first validated Ada implementation was the NYU Ada/Ed translator, certified on April 11, 1983.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] NYU Ada/Ed is implemented in the high-level set language SETL.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Several commercial companies began offering Ada compilers and associated development tools, including Alsys, TeleSoft, DDC-I, Advanced Computer Techniques, Tartan Laboratories, Irvine Compiler, TLD Systems, and Verdix.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] In 1991, the US Department of Defense began to require the use of Ada (the *Ada mandate*) for all software, though exceptions to this rule were often granted.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] The Department of Defense Ada mandate was effectively removed in 1997, as the DoD began to embrace commercial off-the-shelf (COTS) technology.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Similar requirements existed in other NATO countries: Ada was required for NATO systems involving command and control and other functions, and Ada was the mandated or preferred language for defense-related applications in countries such as Sweden, Germany, and Canada.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] By the late 1980s and early 1990s, Ada compilers had improved in performance, but there were still barriers to fully exploiting Ada's abilities, including a tasking model that was different from what most real-time programmers were used to.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] The Canadian Automated Air Traffic System was written in 1 million lines of Ada (SLOC count).
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] It featured advanced distributed processing, a distributed Ada database, and object-oriented design.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Ada is also used in other air traffic systems, e.g., the UK's next-generation Interim Future Area Control Tools Support (iFACTS) air traffic control system is designed and implemented using SPARK Ada.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] It is also used in the French TVM in-cab signalling system on the TGV high-speed rail system, and the metro suburban trains in Paris, London, Hong Kong and New York City.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] The Ada 95 revision of the language went beyond the Steelman requirements, targeting general-purpose systems in addition to embedded ones, and adding features supporting object-oriented programming.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Ada was first published in 1980 as an ANSI standard ANSI/**MIL-STD 1815**.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] As this very first version held many errors and inconsistencies, the revised edition was published in 1983 as ANSI/MIL-STD 1815A.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Without any further changes, it became an ISO standard in 1987.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] This version of the language is commonly known as **Ada 83**, from the date of its adoption by ANSI, but is sometimes referred to also as **Ada 87**, from the date of its adoption by ISO.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] There is also a French translation; DIN translated it into German as DIN 66268 in 1988.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Work has continued on improving and updating the technical content of the Ada language.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] A Technical Corrigendum to Ada 95 was published in October 2001, and a major Amendment, ISO/IEC 8652:1995/Amd 1:2007 was published on March 9, 2007, commonly known as **Ada 2005** because work on the new standard was finished that year.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] The Ada-based SPARK technology has been made possible by the enabling characteristics of the Ada language, including its separation of specification and implementation via packages, its support for user-defined scalar types, and its support for composite type usage without resorting to pointers.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] The Ada 2012 revision was especially important for SPARK, as its support for contracts as a part of the language permitted SPARK to be redesigned from the beginning towards fulfilling its goal of co-developing programs alongside their proofs of correctness.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] On May 2, 2023, the Ada community saw the formal approval of publication of the **Ada 2022** edition of the programming language standard.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Despite the names Ada 83, 95 etc., legally there is only one Ada standard, the last ISO/IEC standard: with the acceptance of a new standard version, the previous one becomes withdrawn.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] The other names are informal ones referencing a certain edition.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Other related standards include ISO/IEC 8651-3:1988 *Information processing systems—Computer graphics—Graphical Kernel System (GKS) language bindings—Part 3: Ada*.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Ada is an ALGOL-like programming language featuring control structures with reserved words such as *if*, *then*, *else*, *while*, *for*, and so on.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] However, Ada also has many data structuring facilities and other abstractions which were not included in the original ALGOL 60, such as type definitions, records, pointers, and enumerations.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Such constructs were in part inherited from or inspired by Pascal.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Ada's type system is not based on a set of predefined primitive types but allows users to declare their own types.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] This declaration in turn is not based on the internal representation of the type but on describing the goal which should be achieved.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] This allows the compiler to determine a suitable memory size for the type, and to check for violations of the type definition at compile time and run time (i.e., range violations, buffer overruns, type consistency, etc.).
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Ada supports numerical types defined by a range, modulo types, aggregate types (records and arrays), and enumeration types.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Access types define a reference to an instance of a specified type; untyped pointers are not permitted.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Special types provided by the language are task types and protected types.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] The predefined plus operator can only add values of the same type, so the expression is illegal.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Types can have modifiers such as *limited, abstract, private* etc.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Private types do not show their inner structure; objects of limited types cannot be copied.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Ada 95 adds further features for object-oriented extension of types.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Ada is a structured programming language, meaning that the flow of control is structured into standard statements.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] All standard constructs and deep-level early exit are supported, so the use of the also supported "go to" commands is seldom needed.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Among the parts of an Ada program are packages, procedures and functions.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Functions differ from procedures in that they must return a value.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Function calls cannot be used "as a statement", and their result must be assigned to a variable.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] However, since Ada 2012, functions are not required to be pure and may mutate their suitably declared parameters or the global state.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Packages, procedures and functions can nest to any depth, and each can also be the logical outermost block.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Each package, procedure or function can have its own declarations of constants, types, variables, and other procedures, functions and packages, which can be declared in any order.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] A pragma is a compiler directive that conveys information to the compiler to allow specific manipulating of compiled output.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Certain pragmas are built into the language, while others are implementation-specific.
[src:legacy-languages/ada-programming-language] Examples of common usage of compiler pragmas would be to disable certain features, such as run-time type checking or array subscript boundary checking, or to instruct the compiler to insert object code instead of a function call (as C/C++ does with inline functions).
[src:legacy-languages/algol] In the sense that the syntax of most modern languages is "Algol-like", it was arguably more influential than three other high-level programming languages among which it was roughly contemporary: FORTRAN, Lisp, and COBOL.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] It was designed to avoid some of the perceived problems with FORTRAN and eventually gave rise to many other programming languages, including PL/I, Simula, BCPL, B, Pascal, Ada, and C.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] ALGOL introduced code blocks and the `begin`...`end` pairs for delimiting them.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] It was also the first language implementing nested function definitions with lexical scope.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] Moreover, it was the first programming language to give detailed attention to formal language definition and, through the *Algol 60 Report*, it introduced Backus–Naur form, a principal formal grammar notation for language design.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] ALGOL 68 is substantially different from ALGOL 60 and was not well received, so reference to "Algol" is generally understood to mean ALGOL 60 and its dialects.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] ALGOL was developed jointly by a committee of European and American computer scientists in a meeting in 1958 at the Swiss Federal Institute of Technology in Zurich (cf.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] It specified three different syntaxes: a reference syntax, a publication syntax, and an implementation syntax, syntaxes that permitted it to use different keyword names and conventions for decimal points (commas vs periods) for different languages.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] ALGOL 60 did however become the standard for the publication of algorithms and had a profound effect on future language development.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] John Backus developed the *Backus normal form* method of describing programming languages specifically for ALGOL 58.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] It was revised and expanded by Peter Naur for ALGOL 60, and at Donald Knuth's suggestion renamed Backus–Naur form.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] Peter Naur: "As editor of the ALGOL Bulletin I was drawn into the international discussions of the language and was selected to be member of the European language design group in November 1959.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] Alan Perlis gave a vivid description of the meeting: "The meetings were exhausting, interminable, and exhilarating.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] One became aggravated when one's good ideas were discarded along with the bad ones of others.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] Nevertheless, diligence persisted during the entire period.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] A significant contribution of the ALGOL 58 Report was to provide standard terms for programming concepts: statement, declaration, type, label, primary, block, and others.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] ALGOL 60 inspired many languages that followed it.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] ALGOL 60 as officially defined had no I/O facilities; implementations defined their own in ways that were rarely compatible with each other.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] In contrast, ALGOL 68 offered an extensive library of *transput* (input/output) facilities.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] ALGOL 60 allowed for two evaluation strategies for parameter passing: the common call-by-value, and call-by-name.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] Call-by-name has certain effects in contrast to call-by-reference.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] For example, without specifying the parameters as *value* or *reference*, it is impossible to develop a procedure that will swap the values of two parameters if the actual parameters that are passed in are an integer variable and an array that is indexed by that same integer variable.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] Think of passing a pointer to swap(i, A[i]) in to a function.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] Now that every time swap is referenced, it is reevaluated.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] Say i := 1 and A[i] := 2, so every time swap is referenced it will return the other combination of the values ([1,2], [2,1], [1,2] and so on).
[src:legacy-languages/algol] A similar situation occurs with a random function passed as actual argument.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] Call-by-name is known by many compiler designers for the interesting "thunks" that are used to implement it.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] Donald Knuth devised the "man or boy test" to separate compilers that correctly implemented "recursion and non-local references." This test contains an example of call-by-name.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] ALGOL 68 was defined using a two-level grammar formalism invented by Adriaan van Wijngaarden and which bears his name.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] (The way the bold text has to be written depends on the implementation, e.g.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] 'INTEGER'—quotation marks included—for integer.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] Here is an example of how to produce a table using Elliott 803 ALGOL.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] The following code samples are ALGOL 68 versions of the above ALGOL 60 code samples.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] ALGOL 68 implementations used ALGOL 60's approaches to stropping.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] In ALGOL 68's case tokens with the bold typeface are reserved words, types (modes) or operators.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] Note: lower (⌊) and upper (⌈) bounds of an array, and array slicing, are directly available to the programmer.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] The variations and lack of portability of the programs from one implementation to another is easily demonstrated by the classic hello world program.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] Since ALGOL 60 had no I/O facilities, there is no portable hello world program in ALGOL.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] The next three examples are in Burroughs Extended Algol.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] The first two direct output at the interactive terminal they are run on.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] The first uses a character array, similar to C.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] The language allows the array identifier to be used as a pointer to the array, and hence in a REPLACE statement.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] An even simpler program using the Display statement.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] An alternative example, using Elliott Algol I/O is as follows.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] Elliott Algol used different characters for "open-string-quote" and "close-string-quote", represented here by ‘ and ’ .
[src:legacy-languages/algol] Below is a version from Elliott 803 Algol (A104).
[src:legacy-languages/algol] The standard Elliott 803 used five-hole paper tape and thus only had upper case.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] The code lacked any quote characters so £ (UK Pound Sign) was used for open quote and ?
[src:legacy-languages/algol] Special sequences were placed in double quotes (e.g£. £L?? produced a new line on the teleprinter).
[src:legacy-languages/algol] The ICT 1900 series Algol I/O version allowed input from paper tape or punched card.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] Paper tape 'full' mode allowed lower case.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] The open and close quote characters were represented using '(' and ')' and spaces by %.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] In the language of the "Algol 68 Report" the input/output facilities were collectively called the "Transput".
[src:legacy-languages/algol] The ALGOLs were conceived at a time when character sets were diverse and evolving rapidly; also, the ALGOLs were defined so that only *uppercase* letters were required.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] 1960: IFIP – The Algol 60 language and report included several mathematical symbols which are available on modern computers and operating systems, but, unfortunately, were unsupported on most computing systems at the time.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] 1961 September: ASCII – The ASCII character set, then in an early stage of development, had the \ (Back slash) character added to it in order to support ALGOL's Boolean operators /\ and \/.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] 1962: ALCOR – This character set included the unusual "᛭" runic cross character for multiplication and the "⏨" Decimal Exponent Symbol for floating point notation.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] 1964: GOST – The 1964 Soviet standard GOST 10859 allowed the encoding of 4-bit, 5-bit, 6-bit and 7-bit characters in ALGOL.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] 1968: The "Algol 68 Report" – used extant ALGOL characters, and further adopted →, ↓, ↑, □, ⌊, ⌈, ⎩, ⎧, ○, ⊥, and ¢ characters which can be found on the IBM 2741 keyboard with *typeball* (or *golf ball*) print heads inserted (such as the APL golf ball).
[src:legacy-languages/algol] These became available in the mid-1960s while ALGOL 68 was being drafted.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] The report was translated into Russian, German, French, and Bulgarian, and allowed programming in languages with larger character sets, e.g., Cyrillic alphabet of the Soviet BESM-4.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] All ALGOL's characters are also part of the Unicode standard and most of them are available in several popular fonts.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] 2009 October: Unicode – The `⏨` (Decimal Exponent Symbol) for floating-point notation was added to Unicode 5.2 for backward compatibility with historic Buran programme ALGOL software.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] To date there have been at least 70 augmentations, extensions, derivations and sublanguages of Algol 60.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] The Burroughs dialects included special Bootstrapping dialects such as ESPOL and NEWP.
[src:legacy-languages/algol] The latter is still used for Unisys MCP system software.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] A mathematical notation for manipulating arrays was developed by Kenneth E.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Iverson, starting in 1957 at Harvard University.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] In 1960, he began work for IBM where he developed this notation with Adin Falkoff and published it in his book *A Programming Language* in 1962.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] This notation was used inside IBM for short research reports on computer systems, such as the Burroughs B5000 and its stack mechanism when stack machines versus register machines were being evaluated by IBM for upcoming computers.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Iverson also used his notation in a draft of the chapter *A Programming Language*, written for a book he was writing with Fred Brooks, *Automatic Data Processing*, which would be published in 1963.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] In 1979, Iverson received the Turing Award for his work on APL.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] As early as 1962, the first attempt to use the notation to describe a complete computer system happened after Falkoff discussed with William C.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Carter his work to standardize the instruction set for the machines that later became the IBM System/360 family.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] In 1963, Herbert Hellerman, working at the IBM Systems Research Institute, implemented a part of the notation on an IBM 1620 computer, and it was used by students in a special high school course on calculating transcendental functions by series summation.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Students tested their code in Hellerman's lab.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] This implementation of a part of the notation was called Personalized Array Translator (PAT).
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] In 1963, Falkoff, Iverson, and Edward H.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Sussenguth Jr., all working at IBM, used the notation for a formal description of the IBM System/360 series machine architecture and functionality, which resulted in a paper published in *IBM Systems Journal* in 1964.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] After this was published, the team turned their attention to an implementation of the notation on a computer system.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] One of the motivations for this focus of implementation was the interest of John L.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Lawrence who had new duties with Science Research Associates, an educational company bought by IBM in 1964.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Lawrence asked Iverson and his group to help use the language as a tool to develop and use computers in education.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Abrams of Stanford University joined the team at IBM Research, they continued their prior work on an implementation programmed in FORTRAN IV for a part of the notation which had been done for the IBM 7090 computer running on the IBSYS operating system.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] This work was finished in late 1965 and later named IVSYS (for Iverson system).
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] The basis of this implementation was described in detail by Abrams in a Stanford University Technical Report, "An Interpreter for Iverson Notation" in 1966.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] The academic aspect of this was formally supervised by Niklaus Wirth.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Like Hellerman's PAT system earlier, this implementation omitted the APL character set, but used special English reserved words for functions and operators.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] The system was later adapted for a time-sharing system and, by November 1966, it had been reprogrammed for the IBM System/360 Model 50 computer running in a time-sharing mode and was used internally at IBM.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] A key development in the ability to use APL effectively, before the wide use of cathode-ray tube (CRT) terminals, was the development of a special IBM Selectric typewriter interchangeable typing element with all the special APL characters on it.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] This was used on paper printing terminal workstations using the Selectric typewriter and typing element mechanism, such as the IBM 1050 and IBM 2741 terminal.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Keycaps could be placed over the normal keys to show which APL characters would be entered and typed when that key was struck.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] For the first time, a programmer could type in and see proper APL characters as used in Iverson's notation and not be forced to use awkward English keyword representations of them.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Falkoff and Iverson had the special APL Selectric typing elements, 987 and 988, designed in late 1964, although no APL computer system was available to use them.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Iverson cited Falkoff as the inspiration for the idea of using an IBM Selectric typing element for the APL character set.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Many APL symbols, even with the APL characters on the Selectric typing element, still had to be typed in by over-striking two extant element characters.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] An example is the *grade up* character, which had to be made from a *delta* (shift-H) and a *Sheffer stroke* (shift-M).
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] This was necessary because the APL character set was much larger than the 88 characters allowed on the typing element, even when letters were restricted to upper-case (capitals).
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] The Tektronix 4013 Computer Display Terminal is a Tektronix 4010 with both the APL and ASCII character sets.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] There is a rocker switch above the keys to select the character set.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] The first APL interactive login and creation of an APL workspace was in 1966 by Larry Breed using an IBM 1050 terminal at the IBM Mohansic Labs near Thomas J.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Watson Research Center, the home of APL, in Yorktown Heights, New York.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] IBM was chiefly responsible for introducing APL to the marketplace.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] The first publicly available version of APL was released in 1968 for the IBM 1130.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] IBM provided *APL\1130* for free but without liability or support.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] It would run in as little as 8k 16-bit words of memory, and used a dedicated 1 megabyte hard disk.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] APL gained its foothold on mainframe timesharing systems from the late 1960s through the early 1980s, in part because it would support multiple users on lower-specification systems that had no dynamic address translation hardware.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Additional improvements in performance for selected IBM System/370 mainframe systems included the *APL Assist Microcode* in which some support for APL execution was included in the processor's firmware, as distinct from being implemented entirely by higher-level software.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Somewhat later, as suitably performing hardware was finally growing available in the mid- to late-1980s, many users migrated their applications to the personal computer environment.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Early IBM APL interpreters for IBM 360 and IBM 370 hardware implemented their own multi-user management instead of relying on the host services, thus they were their own timesharing systems.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] First introduced for use at IBM in 1966, the *APL\360* system was a multi-user interpreter.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] The ability to programmatically communicate with the operating system for information and setting interpreter system variables was done through special privileged "I-beam" functions, using both monadic and dyadic operations.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] In 1973, IBM released *APL.SV*, which was a continuation of the same product, but which offered shared variables as a means to access facilities outside of the APL system, such as operating system files.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] In the mid-1970s, the IBM mainframe interpreter was even adapted for use on the IBM 5100 desktop computer, which had a small CRT and an APL keyboard, when most other small computers of the time only offered BASIC.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] In the 1980s, the *VSAPL* program product enjoyed wide use with Conversational Monitor System (CMS), Time Sharing Option (TSO), VSPC, MUSIC/SP, and CICS users.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Hagerty directed the implementation of the University of Maryland APL interpreter for the 1100 line of the Sperry UNIVAC 1100/2200 series mainframe computers.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] In 1974, student Alan Stebbens was assigned the task of implementing an internal function.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Xerox APL was available from June 1975 for Xerox 560 and Sigma 6, 7, and 9 mainframes running CP-V and for Honeywell CP-6.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] In the 1960s and 1970s, several timesharing firms arose that sold APL services using modified versions of the IBM APL\360 interpreter.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] In North America, the better-known ones were IP Sharp Associates, Scientific Time Sharing Corporation (STSC), Time Sharing Resources (TSR), and The Computer Company (TCC).
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] CompuServe also entered the market in 1978 with an APL Interpreter based on a modified version of Digital Equipment Corp and Carnegie Mellon's, which ran on DEC's KI and KL 36-bit machines.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] CompuServe's APL was available both to its commercial market and the consumer information service.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] With the advent first of less expensive mainframes such as the IBM 4300, and later the personal computer, by the mid-1980s, the timesharing industry was all but gone.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] APL interpreters were available from other mainframe and mini-computer manufacturers also, notably Burroughs, Control Data Corporation (CDC), Data General, Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC), Harris, Hewlett-Packard (HP), Siemens, Xerox and others.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Garth Foster of Syracuse University sponsored regular meetings of the APL implementers' community at Syracuse's Minnowbrook Conference Center in Blue Mountain Lake, New York.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] In later years, Eugene McDonnell organized similar meetings at the Asilomar Conference Grounds near Monterey, California, and at Pajaro Dunes near Watsonville, California.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] The SIGAPL special interest group of the Association for Computing Machinery continues to support the APL community.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] On microcomputers, which became available from the mid-1970s onwards, BASIC became the dominant programming language.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Nevertheless, some microcomputers provided APL instead – the first being the Intel 8008-based MCM/70 which was released in 1974 and which was primarily used in education.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Another machine of this time was the VideoBrain Family Computer, released in 1977, which was supplied with its dialect of APL called APL/S.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] The Commodore SuperPET, introduced in 1981, included an APL interpreter developed by the University of Waterloo.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] In 1976, Bill Gates claimed in his Open Letter to Hobbyists that Microsoft Corporation was implementing APL for the Intel 8080 and Motorola 6800 but had "very little incentive to make [it] available to hobbyists" because of software piracy.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Ken Iverson, no longer in control of the development of the APL language, left IBM and joined I.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Sharp Associates, where one of his major contributions was directing the evolution of Sharp APL to be more in accord with his vision.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] APL2 was first released for CMS and TSO in 1984.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] The APL2 Workstation edition (Windows, OS/2, AIX, Linux, and Solaris) followed later.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] As other vendors were busy developing APL interpreters for new hardware, notably Unix-based microcomputers, APL2 was almost always the standard chosen for new APL interpreter developments.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Even today, most APL vendors or their users cite APL2 compatibility as a selling point for those products.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] IBM cites its use for problem solving, system design, prototyping, engineering and scientific computations, expert systems, for teaching mathematics and other subjects, visualization and database access.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Various implementations of APL by APLX, Dyalog, et al., include extensions for object-oriented programming, support for .NET, XML-array conversion primitives, graphing, operating system interfaces, and lambda calculus expressions.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Freeware versions include GNU APL for Linux and NARS2000 for Windows (which also runs on Linux under Wine).
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Both of these are fairly complete versions of APL2 with various language extensions.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] APL has been criticized and praised for its choice of a unique character set.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] In the 1960s and 1970s, few terminal devices or even displays could reproduce the APL character set.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] The most popular ones employed the IBM Selectric print mechanism used with a special APL type element.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] One of the early APL line terminals (line-mode operation only, *not* full screen) was the Texas Instruments TI Model 745 (c.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] 1977) with the full APL character set which featured half and full duplex telecommunications modes, for interacting with an APL time-sharing service or remote mainframe to run a remote computer job, remote job entry (RJE).
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Over time, with the universal use of high-quality graphic displays, printing devices and Unicode support, the APL character font problem has largely been eliminated.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] However, entering APL characters requires the use of input method editors, keyboard mappings, virtual/on-screen APL symbol sets, or easy-reference printed keyboard cards which can frustrate beginners accustomed to other programming languages.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] With beginners who have no prior experience with other programming languages, a study involving high school students found that typing and using APL characters did not hinder the students in any measurable way.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] In defense of APL, it requires fewer characters to type, and keyboard mappings become memorized over time.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Special APL keyboards are also made and in use today, as are freely downloadable fonts for operating systems such as Microsoft Windows.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] The reported productivity gains assume that one spends enough time working in the language to make it worthwhile to memorize the symbols, their semantics, keyboard mappings, and many idioms for common tasks.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Unlike traditionally structured programming languages, APL code is typically structured as chains of monadic or dyadic functions, and operators acting on arrays.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] APL has many nonstandard *primitives* (functions and operators) that are indicated by a single symbol or a combination of a few symbols.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] All primitives are defined to have the same precedence, and always associate to the right.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Thus, APL is *read* or best understood from right-to-left.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] 1970 or so) had no programming loop control flow structures, such as `do` or `while` loops, and `if-then-else` constructs.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Instead, they used array operations, and use of structured programming constructs was often unneeded, since an operation could be performed on a full array in one statement.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] For example, the `iota` function (`ι`) can replace for-loop iteration: ιN when applied to a scalar positive integer yields a one-dimensional array (vector), 1 2 3 ...
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Later APL implementations generally include comprehensive control structures, so that data structure and program control flow can be clearly and cleanly separated.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] The APL environment is called a *workspace*.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] In a workspace the user can define programs and data, i.e., the data values exist also outside the programs, and the user can also manipulate the data without having to define a program.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] In the examples below, the APL interpreter first types six spaces before awaiting the user's input.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] The user can save the workspace with all values, programs, and execution status.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] APL uses a set of non-ASCII symbols, which are an extension of traditional arithmetic and algebraic notation.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Having single character names for single instruction, multiple data (SIMD) vector functions is one way that APL enables compact formulation of algorithms for data transformation such as computing Conway's Game of Life in one line of code.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] In nearly all versions of APL, it is theoretically possible to express any computable function in one expression, that is, in one line of code.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Due to the unusual character set, many programmers use special keyboards with APL keytops to write APL code.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Although there are various ways to write APL code using only ASCII characters, in practice it is almost never done.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] (This may be thought to support Iverson's thesis about notation as a tool of thought.) Most if not all modern implementations use standard keyboard layouts, with special mappings or input method editors to access non-ASCII characters.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Historically, the APL font has been distinctive, with uppercase italic alphabetic characters and upright numerals and symbols.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Most vendors continue to display the APL character set in a custom font.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Advocates of APL claim that the examples of so-called *write-only code* (badly written and almost incomprehensible code) are almost invariably examples of poor programming practice or novice mistakes, which can occur in any language.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Advocates also claim that they are far more productive with APL than with more conventional computer languages, and that working software can be implemented in far less time and with far fewer programmers than using other technology.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] They also may claim that because it is compact and terse, APL lends itself well to larger-scale software development and complexity, because the number of lines of code can be reduced greatly.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Many APL advocates and practitioners also view standard programming languages such as COBOL and Java as being comparatively tedious.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] APL is often found where time-to-market is important, such as with trading systems.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] APL makes a clear distinction between *functions* and *operators*.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Functions take arrays (variables or constants or expressions) as arguments, and return arrays as results.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Operators (similar to higher-order functions) take functions or arrays as arguments, and derive related functions.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] For example, the *sum* function is derived by applying the *reduction* operator to the *addition* function.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Applying the same reduction operator to the *maximum* function (which returns the larger of two numbers) derives a function which returns the largest of a group (vector) of numbers.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] In the J language, Iverson substituted the terms *verb* for *function* and *adverb* or *conjunction* for *operator*.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] APL also identifies those features built into the language, and represented by a symbol, or a fixed combination of symbols, as *primitives*.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Most primitives are either functions or operators.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Coding APL is largely a process of writing non-primitive functions and (in some versions of APL) operators.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] However a few primitives are considered to be neither functions nor operators, most noticeably assignment.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Some words used in APL literature have meanings that differ from those in both mathematics and the generality of computer science.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] APL has explicit representations of functions, operators, and syntax, thus providing a basis for the clear and explicit statement of extended facilities in the language, and tools to experiment on them.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] A design theme in APL is to define default actions in some cases that would produce syntax errors in most other programming languages.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] The 'Hello, world' string constant above displays, because display is the default action on any expression for which no action is specified explicitly (e.g. assignment, function parameter).
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Another example of this theme is that exponentiation in APL is written as `2*3`, which indicates raising 2 to the power 3 (this would be written as `2^3` or `2**3` in some languages, or relegated to a function call such as `pow(2, 3);` in others).
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Many languages use `*` to signify multiplication, as in `2*3`, but APL chooses to use `2×3`.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] However, if no base is specified (as with the statement `*3` in APL, or `^3` in other languages), most programming languages one would see this as a syntax error.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] APL, however, assumes the missing base to be the natural logarithm constant e, and interprets `*3` as `2.71828*3`.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Suppose that `X` is an array of numbers.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Reading *right-to-left*, `⍴X` gives the number of elements in X, and since `÷` is a dyadic operator, the term to its left is required as well.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] It is surrounded by parentheses since otherwise X would be taken (so that the summation would be of `X÷⍴X`—each element of X divided by the number of elements in X), and `+/X` gives the sum of the elements of X.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Naturally, one would define this expression as a function for repeated use rather than rewriting it each time.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] The above does a lot, concisely, although it may seem complex to a new APLer.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Since there is no function to the left of the left-most x to tell APL what to do with the result, it simply outputs it to the display (on a single line, separated by spaces) without needing any explicit instruction to do that.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] `?` also has a monadic equivalent called `roll`, which simply returns one random integer between 1 and its sole operand [to the right of it], inclusive.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Thus, a role-playing game program might use the expression `?20` to roll a twenty-sided die.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] The following expression finds all prime numbers from 1 to R.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] In both time and space, the calculation complexity is $O(R^{2})\,\!$ (in Big O notation).
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] (This assumes the APL origin is 1, i.e., indices start with 1.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] The following function "life", written in Dyalog APL, takes a Boolean matrix and calculates the new generation according to Conway's Game of Life.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] It demonstrates the power of APL to implement a complex algorithm in very little code, but understanding it requires some advanced knowledge of APL (as the same program would in many languages).
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] APL derives its name from the initials of Iverson's book *A Programming Language*, even though the book describes Iverson's mathematical notation, rather than the implemented programming language described in this article.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] The name is used only for actual implementations, starting with APL\360.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] There has always been cooperation between APL vendors, and joint conferences were held on a regular basis from 1969 until 2010.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] At such conferences, APL merchandise was often handed out, featuring APL motifs or collection of vendor logos.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Common were apples (as a pun on the similarity in pronunciation of *apple* and *APL*) and the code snippet `⍺*⎕` which are the symbols produced by the classic APL keyboard layout when holding the APL modifier key and typing "APL".
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Despite all these community efforts, no universal vendor-agnostic logo for the programming language emerged.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] APL is used for many purposes including financial and insurance applications, artificial intelligence, neural networks and robotics.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] It has been argued that APL is a calculation tool and not a programming language; its symbolic nature and array capabilities have made it popular with domain experts and data scientists who do not have or require the skills of a computer programmer.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] APL is well suited to image manipulation and computer animation, where graphic transformations can be encoded as matrix multiplications.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] One of the first commercial computer graphics houses, Digital Effects, produced an APL graphics product named *Visions*, which was used to create television commercials and animation for the 1982 film *Tron*.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Latterly, the Stormwind boating simulator uses APL to implement its core logic, its interfacing to the rendering pipeline middleware and a major part of its physics engine.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Today, APL remains in use in a wide range of commercial and scientific applications, asset management, health care, and DNA profiling.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] The first implementation of APL using recognizable APL symbols was APL\360 which ran on the IBM System/360, and was completed in November 1966 though at that time remained in use only within IBM.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] In 1973 its implementors, Larry Breed, Dick Lathwell and Roger Moore, were awarded the Grace Murray Hopper Award from the Association for Computing Machinery (ACM).
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] In 1975, the IBM 5100 microcomputer offered APL\360 as one of two built-in ROM-based interpreted languages for the computer, complete with a keyboard and display that supported all the special symbols used in the language.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Significant developments to APL\360 included CMS/APL, which made use of the virtual storage capabilities of CMS and APLSV, which introduced shared variables, system variables and system functions.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] It was subsequently ported to the IBM System/370 and VSPC platforms until its final release in 1983, after which it was replaced by APL2.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] In 1968, APL\1130 became the first publicly available APL system, created by IBM for the IBM 1130.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] It became the most popular IBM Type-III Library software that IBM released.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] APL*Plus and Sharp APL are versions of APL\360 with added business-oriented extensions such as data formatting and facilities to store APL arrays in external files.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] They were jointly developed by two companies, employing various members of the original IBM APL\360 development team.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Sharp Associates (IPSA), an APL\360 services company formed in 1964 by Ian Sharp, Roger Moore and others, and STSC, a time-sharing and consulting service company formed in 1969 by Lawrence Breed and others.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Together the two developed APL*Plus and thereafter continued to work together but develop APL separately as APL*Plus and Sharp APL.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] STSC ported APL*Plus to many platforms with versions being made for the VAX 11, PC and UNIX, whereas IPSA took a different approach to the arrival of the personal computer and made Sharp APL available on this platform using additional PC-XT/360 hardware.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] In 1993, Soliton Incorporated was formed to support Sharp APL and it developed Sharp APL into SAX (Sharp APL for Unix).
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] As of 2018, APL*Plus continues as APL2000 APL+Win.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] In 1985, Ian Sharp, and Dan Dyer of STSC, jointly received the Kenneth E.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Iverson Award for Outstanding Contribution to APL.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] APL2 was a significant re-implementation of APL by IBM which was developed from 1971 and first released in 1984.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] It provides many additions to the language, of which the most notable is nested (non-rectangular) array support.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] The entire APL2 Products and Services Team was awarded the Iverson Award in 2007.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] In 2021, IBM sold APL2 to Log-On Software, who develop and sell the product as *Log-On APL2*.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] In 1972, APLGOL was released as an experimental version of APL that added structured programming language constructs to the language framework.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] New statements were added for interstatement control, conditional statement execution, and statement structuring, as well as statements to clarify the intent of the algorithm.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] It was implemented for Hewlett-Packard in 1977.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Dyalog APL was first released by British company Dyalog Ltd. in 1983 and, as of 2018, is available for AIX, Linux (including on the Raspberry Pi), macOS and Microsoft Windows platforms.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] It is based on APL2, with extensions to support object-oriented programming, functional programming, and tacit programming.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Licences are free for personal/non-commercial use.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] In 1995, two of the development team – John Scholes and Peter Donnelly – were awarded the Iverson Award for their work on the interpreter.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Gitte Christensen and Morten Kromberg were joint recipients of the Iverson Award in 2016.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] NARS2000 is an open-source APL interpreter written by Bob Smith, a prominent APL developer and implementor from STSC in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] NARS2000 contains advanced features and new datatypes and runs natively on Microsoft Windows, and other platforms under Wine.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] It is named after a development tool from the 1980s, NARS (Nested Arrays Research System).
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] APLX is a cross-platform dialect of APL, based on APL2 and with several extensions, which was first released by British company MicroAPL in 2002.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Although no longer in development or on commercial sale it is now available free of charge from Dyalog.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] York APL was developed at the York University, Ontario around 1968, running on IBM 360 mainframes.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] One notable difference between it and APL\360 was that it defined the "shape" (ρ) of a scalar as 1 whereas APL\360 defined it as the more mathematically correct 0 — this made it easier to write functions that acted the same with scalars and vectors.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] GNU APL is a free implementation of Extended APL as specified in ISO/IEC 13751:2001 and is thus an implementation of APL2.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] It runs on Linux, macOS, several BSD dialects, and on Windows (either using Cygwin for full support of all its system functions or as a native 64-bit Windows binary with some of its system functions missing).
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] GNU APL uses Unicode internally and can be scripted.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Richard Stallman, founder of the GNU Project, was an early adopter of APL, using it to write a text editor as a high school student in the summer of 1969.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] APL is traditionally an interpreted language, having language characteristics such as weak variable typing not well suited to compilation.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Most APL interpreters support idiom recognition and evaluate common idioms as single operations.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] For example, by evaluating the idiom `BV/⍳⍴A` as a single operation (where `BV` is a Boolean vector and `A` is an array), the creation of two intermediate arrays is avoided.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Weak typing in APL means that a name may reference an array (of any datatype), a function or an operator.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] In general, the interpreter cannot know in advance which form it will be and must therefore perform analysis, syntax checking etc. at run-time.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] However, in certain circumstances, it is possible to deduce in advance what type a name is expected to reference and then generate bytecode which can be executed with reduced run-time overhead.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] This bytecode can also be optimised using compilation techniques such as constant folding or common subexpression elimination.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] The interpreter will execute the bytecode when present and when any assumptions which have been made are met.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Dyalog APL includes support for optimised bytecode.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] Compilation of APL has been the subject of research and experiment since the language first became available; the first compiler is considered to be the Burroughs APL-700 which was released around 1971.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] In order to be able to compile APL, language limitations have to be imposed.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] APEX is a research APL compiler which was written by Robert Bernecky and is available under the GNU General Public License.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] APL has been standardized by the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) working group X3J10 and International Organization for Standardization (ISO) and International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), ISO/IEC Joint Technical Committee 1 Subcommittee 22 Working Group 3.
[src:legacy-languages/apl-programming-language] The Core APL language is specified in ISO 8485:1989, and the Extended APL language is specified in ISO/IEC 13751:2001.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] In addition to the programming language, Kemeny and Kurtz developed the Dartmouth Time-Sharing System (DTSS), which allowed multiple users to edit and run BASIC programs simultaneously on remote terminals.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] This general model became popular on minicomputer systems like the PDP-11 and Data General Nova in the late 1960s and early 1970s.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Hewlett-Packard produced an entire computer line for this method of operation, introducing the HP2000 series in the late 1960s and continuing sales into the 1980s.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Many early video games trace their history to one of these versions of BASIC.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] The emergence of microcomputers in the mid-1970s led to the development of multiple BASIC dialects, including Microsoft BASIC in 1975.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Due to the tiny main memory available on these machines, often 4 KB, a variety of Tiny BASIC dialects were also created.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] BASIC was available for almost any system of the era and became the *de facto* programming language for home computer systems that emerged in the late 1970s.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] These PCs almost always had a BASIC interpreter installed by default, often in the machine's firmware or sometimes on a ROM cartridge.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] BASIC declined in popularity in the 1990s, as more powerful microcomputers came to market and programming languages with advanced features (such as Pascal and C) became tenable on such computers.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] By then, most nontechnical personal computer users relied on pre-written applications rather than writing their own programs.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] In 1991, Microsoft released Visual Basic, combining an updated version of BASIC with a visual forms builder.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] This reignited use of the language and "VB" remains a major programming language in the form of VB.NET, while a hobbyist scene for BASIC more broadly continues to exist.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Kemeny was the chairman of the Dartmouth College Mathematics Department.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Based largely on his reputation as an innovator in math teaching, in 1959 the college won an Alfred P.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Sloan Foundation award for $500,000 to build a new department building.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Kurtz had joined the department in 1956, and from the 1960s Kemeny and Kurtz agreed on the need for programming literacy among students outside the traditional STEM fields.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Kemeny later noted that "Our vision was that every student on campus should have access to a computer, and any faculty member should be able to use a computer in the classroom whenever appropriate.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Kemeny and Kurtz had made two previous experiments with simplified languages, DARSIMCO (Dartmouth Simplified Code) and DOPE (Dartmouth Oversimplified Programming Experiment).
[src:legacy-languages/basic] These did not progress past a single freshman class.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] New experiments using Fortran and ALGOL followed, but Kurtz concluded these languages were too tricky for what they desired.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] As Kurtz noted, Fortran had numerous oddly formed commands, notably an "almost impossible-to-memorize convention for specifying a loop: `DO 100 I = 1, 10, 2`.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Moreover, the lack of any sort of immediate feedback was a key problem; the machines of the era used batch processing and took a long time to complete a run of a program.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] While Kurtz was visiting MIT, John McCarthy suggested that time-sharing offered a solution; a single machine could divide up its processing time among many users, giving them the illusion of having a (slow) computer to themselves.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Small programs would return results in a few seconds.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] This led to increasing interest in a system using time-sharing and a new language specifically for use by non-STEM students.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Kemeny wrote the first version of BASIC.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] The acronym *BASIC* comes from the name of an unpublished paper by Thomas Kurtz.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] The new language was heavily patterned on FORTRAN II; statements were one-to-a-line, numbers were used to indicate the target of loops and branches, and many of the commands were similar or identical to Fortran.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] However, the syntax was changed wherever it could be improved.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] For instance, the difficult to remember `DO` loop was replaced by the much easier to remember `FOR I = 1 TO 10 STEP 2`, and the line number used in the DO was instead indicated by the `NEXT I`.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Likewise, the cryptic `IF` statement of Fortran, whose syntax matched a particular instruction of the machine on which it was originally written, became the simpler `IF I=5 THEN GOTO 100`.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] These changes made the language much less idiosyncratic while still having an overall structure and feel similar to the original FORTRAN.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] The project received a $300,000 grant from the National Science Foundation, which was used to purchase a GE-225 computer for processing, and a Datanet-30 realtime processor to handle the Teletype Model 33 teleprinters used for input and output.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] A team of a dozen undergraduates worked on the project for about a year, writing both the DTSS system and the BASIC compiler.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] The first version BASIC language was released on 1 May 1964.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Initially, BASIC concentrated on supporting straightforward mathematical work, with matrix arithmetic support from its initial implementation as a batch language, and character string functionality being added by 1965.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Usage in the university rapidly expanded, requiring the main CPU to be replaced by a GE-235, and still later by a GE-635.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] By the early 1970s there were hundreds of terminals connected to the machines at Dartmouth, some of them remotely.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Wanting use of the language to become widespread, its designers made the compiler available free of charge.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] In the 1960s, software became a chargeable commodity; until then, it was provided without charge as a service with expensive computers, usually available only to lease.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] They also made it available to high schools in the Hanover, New Hampshire, area and regionally throughout New England on Teletype Model 33 and Model 35 teleprinter terminals connected to Dartmouth via dial-up phone lines, and they put considerable effort into promoting the language.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] In the following years, as other dialects of BASIC appeared, Kemeny and Kurtz's original BASIC dialect became known as *Dartmouth BASIC*.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] New Hampshire recognized the accomplishment in 2019 when it erected a highway historical marker in Hanover describing the creation of "the first user-friendly programming language".
[src:legacy-languages/basic] The emergence of BASIC took place as part of a wider movement toward time-sharing systems.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] First conceptualized during the late 1950s, the idea became so dominant in the computer industry by the early 1960s that its proponents were speaking of a future in which users would "buy time on the computer much the same way that the average household buys power and water from utility companies".
[src:legacy-languages/basic] General Electric, having worked on the Dartmouth project, wrote their own underlying operating system and launched an online time-sharing system known as Mark I.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] It featured BASIC as one of its primary selling points.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Other companies in the emerging field quickly followed suit; Tymshare introduced SUPER BASIC in 1968, CompuServe had a version on the DEC-10 at their launch in 1969, and by the early 1970s BASIC was largely universal on general-purpose mainframe computers.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Even IBM eventually joined the club with the introduction of VS-BASIC in 1973.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Although time-sharing services with BASIC were successful for a time, the widespread success predicted earlier was not to be.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] The emergence of minicomputers during the same period, and especially low-cost microcomputers in the mid-1970s, allowed anyone to purchase and run their own systems rather than buy online time which was typically billed at dollars per minute.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] BASIC, by its very nature of being small, was naturally suited to porting to the minicomputer market, which was emerging at the same time as the time-sharing services.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] These machines had small main memory, perhaps as little as 4 KB in modern terminology, and lacked high-performance storage like hard drives that make compilers practical.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] On these systems, BASIC was normally implemented as an interpreter rather than a compiler due to its lower requirement for working memory.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] A particularly important example was HP Time-Shared BASIC, which, like the original Dartmouth system, used two computers working together to implement a time-sharing system.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] The first, a low-end machine in the HP 2100 series, was used to control user input and save and load their programs to tape or disk.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] The other, a high-end version of the same underlying machine, ran the programs and generated output.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] For a cost of about $100,000, one could own a machine capable of running between 16 and 32 users at the same time.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] The system, bundled as the HP 2000, was the first mini platform to offer time-sharing and was an immediate runaway success, catapulting HP to become the third-largest vendor in the minicomputer space, behind DEC and Data General (DG).
[src:legacy-languages/basic] DEC, the leader in the minicomputer space since the mid-1960s, had initially ignored BASIC.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] This was due to their work with RAND Corporation, who had purchased a PDP-6 to run their JOSS language, which was conceptually very similar to BASIC.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] This led DEC to introduce a smaller, cleaned up version of JOSS known as FOCAL, which they heavily promoted in the late 1960s.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] However, with timesharing systems widely offering BASIC, and all of their competition in the minicomputer space doing the same, DEC's customers were clamoring for BASIC.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] After management repeatedly ignored their pleas, David H.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Ahl took it upon himself to buy a BASIC for the PDP-8, which was a major success in the education market.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] By the early 1970s, FOCAL and JOSS had been forgotten and BASIC had become almost universal in the minicomputer market.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] DEC would go on to introduce their updated version, BASIC-PLUS, for use on the RSTS/E time-sharing operating system.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] During this period a number of simple text-based games were written in BASIC, most notably Mike Mayfield's *Star Trek*.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] David Ahl collected these, some ported from FOCAL, and published them in an educational newsletter he compiled.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] He later collected a number of these into book form, *101 BASIC Computer Games*, published in 1973.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] During the same period, Ahl was involved in the creation of a small computer for education use, an early personal computer.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] When management refused to support the concept, Ahl left DEC in 1974 to found the seminal computer magazine, *Creative Computing*.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] The book remained popular, and was re-published on several occasions.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] The introduction of the first microcomputers in the mid-1970s was the start of explosive growth for BASIC.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] It had the advantage that it was fairly well known to the young designers and computer hobbyists who took an interest in microcomputers, many of whom had seen BASIC on minis or mainframes.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] The first microcomputer version of BASIC was co-written by Bill Gates, Paul Allen and Monte Davidoff for their newly formed company, Micro-Soft.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] This was released by MITS in punch tape format for the Altair 8800 shortly after the machine itself, immediately cementing BASIC as the primary language of early microcomputers.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Members of the Homebrew Computer Club began circulating copies of the program, causing Gates to write his Open Letter to Hobbyists, complaining about this early example of software piracy.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Partially in response to Gates's letter, and partially to make an even smaller BASIC that would run usefully on 4 KB machines, Bob Albrecht urged Dennis Allison to write their own variation of the language.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] How to design and implement a stripped-down version of an interpreter for the BASIC language was covered in articles by Allison in the first three quarterly issues of the *People's Computer Company* newsletter published in 1975 and implementations with source code published in *Dr.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Dobb's Journal of Tiny BASIC Calisthenics & Orthodontia: Running Light Without Overbyte*.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] This led to a wide variety of Tiny BASICs with added features or other improvements, with versions from Tom Pittman and Li-Chen Wang becoming particularly well known.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Micro-Soft, by this time Microsoft, ported their interpreter for the MOS 6502, which quickly become one of the most popular microprocessors of the 8-bit era.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] When new microcomputers began to appear, notably the "1977 trinity" of the TRS-80, Commodore PET and Apple II, they either included a version of the MS code, or quickly introduced new models with it.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Ohio Scientific's personal computers also joined this trend at that time.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] By 1978, MS BASIC was a *de facto* standard and practically every home computer of the 1980s included it in ROM.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Upon boot, a BASIC interpreter in direct mode was presented.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Commodore Business Machines includes Commodore BASIC, based on Microsoft BASIC.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] The Apple II and TRS-80 each have two versions of BASIC: a smaller introductory version with the initial releases of the machines and a Microsoft-based version introduced as interest in the platforms increased.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] As new companies entered the field, additional versions were added that subtly changed the BASIC family.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] The Atari 8-bit computers use the 8 KB Atari BASIC which is not derived from Microsoft BASIC.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Sinclair BASIC was introduced in 1980 with the Sinclair ZX80, and was later extended for the Sinclair ZX81 and the Sinclair ZX Spectrum.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] The BBC-published BBC BASIC, developed by Acorn Computers, incorporates extra structured programming keywords and floating-point features.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] As the popularity of BASIC grew in this period, computer magazines published complete source code in BASIC for video games, utilities, and other programs.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Given BASIC's straightforward nature, it was a simple matter to type in the code from the magazine and execute the program.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Different magazines were published featuring programs for specific computers, though some BASIC programs were considered universal and could be used in machines running any variant of BASIC (sometimes with minor adaptations).
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Many books of type-in programs were also available, and in particular, Ahl published versions of the original 101 BASIC games converted into the Microsoft dialect and published it from *Creative Computing* as *BASIC Computer Games*.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] This book, and its sequels, provided hundreds of ready-to-go programs that could be easily converted to practically any BASIC-running platform.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] The book reached the stores in 1978, just as the home computer market was starting off, and it became the first million-selling computer book.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Later packages, such as Learn to Program BASIC would also have gaming as an introductory focus.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] On the business-focused CP/M computers which soon became widespread in small business environments, Microsoft BASIC (MBASIC) was one of the leading applications.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] In 1978, David Lien published the first edition of *The BASIC Handbook: An Encyclopedia of the BASIC Computer Language*, documenting keywords across over 78 different computers.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] By 1981, the second edition documented keywords from over 250 different computers, showcasing the explosive growth of the microcomputer era.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] When IBM was designing the IBM PC, they followed the paradigm of existing home computers in having a built-in BASIC interpreter.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] In addition they produced the Microsoft QuickBASIC Compiler (1985) for power users and hobbyists, and the Microsoft BASIC Professional Development System (PDS) for professional programmers.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Turbo Pascal-publisher Borland published Turbo Basic 1.0 in 1985 (successor versions were marketed under the name PowerBASIC).
[src:legacy-languages/basic] On Unix-like systems, specialized implementations were created such as XBasic and X11-Basic.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] XBasic was ported to Microsoft Windows as XBLite, and cross-platform variants such as SmallBasic, yabasic, Bywater BASIC, nuBasic, MyBasic, Logic Basic, Liberty BASIC, and wxBasic emerged.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] FutureBASIC and Chipmunk Basic meanwhile targeted the Apple Macintosh, while yab is a version of yabasic optimized for BeOS, ZETA and Haiku.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] These later variations introduced many extensions, such as improved string manipulation and graphics support, access to the file system and additional data types.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] More important were the facilities for structured programming, including additional control structures and proper subroutines supporting local variables.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] The addition of an integrated development environment (IDE) and electronic Help files made the products easier to work with and supported learning tools and school curriculum.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] In 1989, Microsoft Press published *Learn BASIC Now*, a book-and-software system designed to teach BASIC programming to self-taught learners who were using IBM-PC compatible systems and the Apple Macintosh.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] *Learn BASIC Now* included software disks containing the Microsoft QuickBASIC Interpreter and a programming tutorial written by Michael Halvorson and David Rygmyr.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Learning systems like *Learn BASIC Now* popularized structured BASIC and helped QuickBASIC reach an installed base of four million active users.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] By the late 1980s, many users were using pre-made applications written by others rather than learning programming themselves, and professional developers had a wide range of advanced languages available on small computers.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] C and later C++ became the languages of choice for professional "shrink wrap" application development.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] A niche that BASIC continued to fill was for hobbyist video game development, as game creation systems and readily available game engines were still in their infancy.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] The Atari ST had STOS BASIC while the Amiga had AMOS BASIC for this purpose.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Microsoft first exhibited BASIC for game development with DONKEY.BAS for GW-BASIC, and later GORILLA.BAS and NIBBLES.BAS for QuickBASIC.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] QBasic maintained an active game development community, which helped later spawn the QB64 and FreeBASIC implementations.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] An early example of this market is the QBasic software package Microsoft Game Shop (1990), a hobbyist-inspired release that included six "arcade-style" games that were easily customizable in QBasic.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] In 2013, a game written in QBasic and compiled with QB64 for modern computers entitled *Black Annex* was released on Steam.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Blitz Basic, Dark Basic, SdlBasic, Super Game System Basic, PlayBASIC, CoolBasic, AllegroBASIC, ethosBASIC, GLBasic and Basic4GL further filled this demand, right up to the modern RCBasic, NaaLaa, AppGameKit, Monkey 2, and Cerberus-X.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] In 1991, Microsoft introduced Visual Basic, an evolutionary development of QuickBASIC.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] It included constructs from that language such as block-structured control statements, parameterized subroutines and optional static typing as well as object-oriented constructs from other languages such as "With" and "For Each".
[src:legacy-languages/basic] The language retained some compatibility with its predecessors, such as the Dim keyword for declarations, "Gosub"/Return statements and optional line numbers which could be used to locate errors.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] An important driver for the development of Visual Basic was as the new macro language for Microsoft Excel, a spreadsheet program.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] To the surprise of many at Microsoft who still initially marketed it as a language for hobbyists, the language came into widespread use for small custom business applications shortly after the release of VB version 3.0, which is widely considered the first relatively stable version.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Microsoft also spun it off as Visual Basic for Applications and Embedded Visual Basic.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Many small business owners found they could create their own small, yet useful applications in a few evenings to meet their own specialized needs.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Eventually, during the lengthy lifetime of VB3, knowledge of Visual Basic had become a marketable job skill.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Microsoft also produced VBScript in 1996 and Visual Basic .NET in 2001.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] The latter has essentially the same power as C# and Java but with syntax that reflects the original Basic language, and also features some cross-platform capability through implementations such as Mono-Basic.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] The IDE, with its event-driven GUI builder, was also influential on other rapid application development tools, most notably Borland Software's Delphi for Object Pascal and its own descendants such as Lazarus.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Mainstream support for the final version 6.0 of the original Visual Basic ended on March 31, 2005, followed by extended support in March 2008.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Owing to its persistent remaining popularity, third-party attempts to further support it exist.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] On February 2, 2017, Microsoft announced that development on VB.NET would no longer be in parallel with that of C#, and on March 11, 2020, it was announced that evolution of the VB.NET language had also concluded.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Even so, the language was still supported.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Many other BASIC dialects have also sprung up since 1990, including the open source QB64 and FreeBASIC, inspired by QBasic, and the Visual Basic-styled RapidQ, HBasic, Basic For Qt and Gambas.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Modern commercial incarnations include PureBasic, PowerBASIC, Xojo, Monkey X and True BASIC (the direct successor to Dartmouth BASIC from a company controlled by Kurtz).
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Several web-based simple BASIC interpreters also now exist, including Microsoft's Small Basic and Google's wwwBASIC.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] A number of compilers also exist that convert BASIC into JavaScript, such as NS Basic.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Building from earlier efforts such as Mobile Basic, many dialects are now available for smartphones and tablets.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] On game consoles, an application for the Nintendo 3DS and Nintendo DSi called *Petit Computer* allows for programming in a slightly modified version of BASIC with DS button support.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] A version has also been released for Nintendo Switch, which has also been supplied a version of the Fuze Code System, a BASIC variant first implemented as a custom Raspberry Pi machine.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Previously BASIC was made available on consoles as Family BASIC (for the Nintendo Famicom) and PSX Chipmunk Basic (for the original PlayStation), while yabasic was ported to the PlayStation 2 and FreeBASIC to the original Xbox.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Variants of BASIC are available on graphing and otherwise programmable calculators made by Texas Instruments (TI-BASIC), HP (HP BASIC), Casio (Casio BASIC), and others.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] QBasic, a version of Microsoft QuickBASIC without the linker to make EXE files, is present in the Windows NT and DOS-Windows 95 streams of operating systems and can be obtained for more recent releases like Windows 7 which do not have them.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Prior to DOS 5, the Basic interpreter was GW-Basic.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] QuickBasic is part of a series of three languages issued by Microsoft for the home and office power user and small-scale professional development; QuickC and QuickPascal are the other two.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] For Windows 95 and 98, which do not have QBasic installed by default, they can be copied from the installation disc, which will have a set of directories for old and optional software; other missing commands like Exe2Bin and others are in these same directories.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] The various Microsoft, Lotus, and Corel office suites and related products are programmable with Visual Basic in one form or another, including LotusScript, which is very similar to VBA 6.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] The Host Explorer terminal emulator uses WWB as a macro language; or more recently the programme and the suite in which it is contained is programmable in an in-house Basic variant known as Hummingbird Basic.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] The VBScript variant is used for programming web content, Outlook 97, Internet Explorer, and the Windows Script Host.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] VBScript is one of the languages that can be accessed by the 4DOS, 4NT, and Take Command enhanced shells.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] SaxBasic and WWB are also very similar to the Visual Basic line of Basic implementations.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] The pre-Office 97 macro language for Microsoft Word is known as WordBASIC.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Excel 4 and 5 use Visual Basic itself as a macro language.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Chipmunk Basic, an interpreter similar to BASICs of the 1970s, is available for Linux, Windows, and macOS.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] The ubiquity of BASIC interpreters on personal computers was such that textbooks once included simple "Try It In BASIC" exercises that encouraged students to experiment with mathematical and computational concepts on classroom or home computers.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Popular computer magazines of the day typically included type-in programs.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Futurist and sci-fi writer David Brin mourned the loss of ubiquitous BASIC in a 2006 *Salon* article as have others who first used computers during this era.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] In turn, the article prompted Microsoft to develop and release Small Basic; it also inspired similar projects like Basic-256 and the web-based Quite Basic.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Dartmouth held a 50th anniversary celebration for BASIC on 1 May 2014.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] The pedagogical use of BASIC has been followed by other languages, such as Pascal, Java and particularly Python.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Dartmouth College celebrated the 50th anniversary of the BASIC language with a day of events on April 30, 2014.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] A short documentary film was produced for the event.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] holds a list of values which are assigned sequentially using the READ command.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Most dialects allow multiple variables as parameters, reading several values in a single operation.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Many dialects allow an optional line number or ordinal value to allow the pointer to be reset to a selected location.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] used to perform comparisons or make decisions.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] , but later versions allowed any valid statement to follow.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] was not widely supported, especially in earlier versions.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] repeat a section of code a given number of times.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] repeat a section of code while the specified condition is true.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] The condition may be evaluated before each iteration of the loop, or after.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Both of these commands are found mostly in later dialects.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] repeat a section of code indefinitely or while/until the specified condition is true.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] , these keywords are mostly found in later dialects.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] jumps to a numbered or labelled line in the program.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] , either after a colon, or on the next line.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] chooses where to jump based on the specified conditions.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] a pair of keywords introduced in the early 1960s to define functions.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] The original BASIC functions were modelled on FORTRAN single-line functions.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] displays the full source code of the current program.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] displays a message on the screen or other output device.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] asks the user to enter the value of a variable.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] The statement may include a prompt message.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] to set the position where the next character will be shown on the screen or printed on paper.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] prints out a number of space characters.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] but moves by a number of additional spaces from the current column rather than moving to a specified column.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] holds a programmer's comment or REMark; often used to give a title to the program and to help identify the purpose of a given section of code.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] , and has a clearly defined method of calling different routines in memory.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] turns on display of each line number as it is run ("TRace ON").
[src:legacy-languages/basic] language, allowing the programmer to intermix high-level and low-level code, typically prefixed with "ASM" or "!" statements.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Minimal versions of BASIC had only integer variables and one- or two-letter variable names, which minimized requirements of limited and expensive memory (RAM).
[src:legacy-languages/basic] More powerful versions had floating-point arithmetic, and variables could be labelled with names six or more characters long.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Keywords could not be used in variables in many early BASICs; "SCORE" would be interpreted as "SC" OR "E", where OR was a keyword.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] String variables are usually distinguished in many microcomputer dialects by having $ suffixed to their name as a sigil, and values are often identified as strings by being delimited by "double quotation marks".
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Arrays in BASIC could contain integers, floating point or string variables.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Some dialects of BASIC supported matrices and matrix operations, which can be used to solve sets of simultaneous linear algebraic equations.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] These dialects would directly support matrix operations such as assignment, addition, multiplication (of compatible matrix types), and evaluation of a determinant.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Many microcomputer BASICs did not support this data type; matrix operations were still possible, but had to be programmed explicitly on array elements.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Note that the `END` statement is optional and has no action in most dialects of BASIC.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] It was not always included, as is the case in this example.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Most home computers BASIC versions, such as MSX BASIC and GW-BASIC, supported simple data types, loop cycles, and arrays.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] The original Dartmouth Basic was unusual in having a matrix keyword, MAT.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Second-generation BASICs (for example, VAX Basic, SuperBASIC, True BASIC, QuickBASIC, BBC BASIC, Pick BASIC, PowerBASIC, Liberty BASIC, QB64 and (arguably) COMAL) introduced a number of features into the language, primarily related to structured and procedure-oriented programming.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Usually, line numbering is omitted from the language and replaced with labels (for GOTO) and procedures to encourage easier and more flexible design.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] In addition keywords and structures to support repetition, selection and procedures with local variables were introduced.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Third-generation BASIC dialects such as Visual Basic, Xojo, Gambas, StarOffice Basic, BlitzMax and PureBasic introduced features to support object-oriented and event-driven programming paradigm.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Most built-in procedures and functions are now represented as *methods* of standard objects rather than *operators*.
[src:legacy-languages/basic] Also, the operating system became increasingly accessible to the BASIC language.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] COBOL's design was started in 1959 by CODASYL and was partly based on the programming language FLOW-MATIC, designed by Grace Hopper.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] It was created as part of a US Department of Defense effort to create a portable programming language for data processing.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] It was originally seen as a stopgap, but the Defense Department promptly pressured computer manufacturers to provide it, resulting in its widespread adoption.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] It was standardized in 1968 and has been revised five times.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Expansions include support for structured and object-oriented programming.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] The current standard is ISO/IEC 1989:2023.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] COBOL statements have prose syntax such as `MOVE x TO y`, which was designed to be self-documenting and highly readable.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] However, it is verbose and uses over 300 reserved words compared to the succinct and mathematically inspired syntax of other languages.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] The COBOL code is split into four *divisions* (identification, environment, data, and procedure), containing a rigid hierarchy of sections, paragraphs, and sentences.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Lacking a large standard library, the standard specifies 43 statements, 87 functions, and just one class.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] COBOL has been criticized for its verbosity, design process, and poor support for structured programming.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] These weaknesses often result in monolithic programs that are hard to comprehend as a whole, despite their local readability.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] For years, COBOL has been assumed as a programming language for business operations in mainframes, although in recent years, many COBOL operations have been moved to cloud computing.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] In the late 1950s, computer users and manufacturers were becoming concerned about the rising cost of programming.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] A 1959 survey had found that in any data processing installation, the programming cost US$800,000 on average and that translating programs to run on new hardware would cost US$600,000.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] At a time when new programming languages were proliferating, the same survey suggested that if a common business-oriented language were used, conversion would be far cheaper and faster.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Hawes, a computer scientist at Burroughs Corporation, called a meeting of representatives from academia, computer users, and manufacturers at the University of Pennsylvania to organize a formal meeting on common business languages.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Representatives included Grace Hopper (inventor of the English-like data processing language FLOW-MATIC), Jean Sammet, and Saul Gorn.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] At the April meeting, the group asked the Department of Defense (DoD) to sponsor an effort to create a common business language.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Phillips, director of the Data System Research Staff at the DoD, who thought that they "thoroughly understood" the DoD's problems.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] The DoD operated 225 computers, had 175 more on order, and had spent over $200 million on implementing programs to run on them.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Portable programs would save time, reduce costs, and ease modernization.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Charles Phillips agreed to sponsor the meeting, and tasked the delegation with drafting the agenda.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] On 28 and 29 May 1959, a meeting was held at the Pentagon to discuss the creation of a common programming language for business (exactly one year after the Zürich ALGOL 58 meeting).
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] It was attended by 41 people and was chaired by Phillips.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] The Department of Defense was concerned about whether it could run the same data processing programs on different computers.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] FORTRAN, the only mainstream language at the time, lacked the features needed to write such programs.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Representatives enthusiastically described a language that could work in a wide variety of environments, from banking and insurance to utilities and inventory control.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] They agreed unanimously that more people should be able to program, and that the new language should not be restricted by the limitations of contemporary technology.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] A majority agreed that the language should make maximal use of English, be capable of change, be machine-independent, and be easy to use, even at the expense of power.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] The meeting resulted in the creation of a steering committee and short, intermediate, and long-range committees.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] The short-range committee was given until September (three months) to produce specifications for an interim language, which would then be improved upon by the other committees.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Their official mission, however, was to identify the strengths and weaknesses of existing programming languages; it did not explicitly direct them to create a new language.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] The deadline was met with disbelief by the short-range committee.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] One member, Betty Holberton, described the three-month deadline as "gross optimism" and doubted that the language really would be a stopgap.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] The steering committee met on 4 June and agreed to name the entire activity the *Committee on Data Systems Languages*, or CODASYL, and to form an executive committee.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] The short-range committee members represented six computer manufacturers and three government agencies.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] The computer manufacturers were Burroughs Corporation, IBM, Minneapolis-Honeywell (Honeywell Labs), RCA, Sperry Rand, and Sylvania Electric Products.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Air Force, the Navy's David Taylor Model Basin, and the National Bureau of Standards (now the National Institute of Standards and Technology).
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] The committee was chaired by Joseph Wegstein of the U.S.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Work began by investigating data descriptions, statements, existing applications, and user experiences.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] The committee mainly examined the FLOW-MATIC, AIMACO, and COMTRAN programming languages.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] The FLOW-MATIC language was particularly influential because it had been implemented and because AIMACO was a derivative of it with only minor changes.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] FLOW-MATIC's inventor, Grace Hopper, also served as a technical adviser to the committee.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] FLOW-MATIC's major contributions to COBOL were long variable names, English words for commands, and the separation of data descriptions and instructions.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] IBM's COMTRAN language, invented by Bob Bemer, was regarded as a competitor to FLOW-MATIC by a short-range committee made up of colleagues of Grace Hopper.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Some of its features were not incorporated into COBOL so that it would not look like IBM had dominated the design process, and Jean Sammet said in 1981 that there had been a "strong anti-IBM bias" from some committee members (herself included).
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] In 1980, Grace Hopper commented that "COBOL 60 is 95% FLOW-MATIC" and that COMTRAN had had an "extremely small" influence.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Furthermore, she said that she would claim that work was influenced by both FLOW-MATIC and COMTRAN only to "keep other people happy [so they] wouldn't try to knock us out.".
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Features from COMTRAN incorporated into COBOL included formulas, the `PICTURE` clause, an improved `IF` statement which obviated the need for GO TOs, and a more robust file management system.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] The usefulness of the committee's work was a subject of great debate.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] While some members thought the language had too many compromises and was the result of design by committee, others felt it was better than the three languages examined.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Some felt the language was too complex; others, too simple.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Controversial features included those some considered useless or too advanced for data processing users.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Such features included Boolean expressions, formulas, and table **subscripts** (indices).
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Another point of controversy was whether to make keywords context-sensitive and the effect that would have on readability.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Although context-sensitive keywords were rejected, the approach was later used in PL/I and partially in COBOL from 2002.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Little consideration was given to interactivity, interaction with operating systems (few existed at that time), and functions (thought of as purely mathematical and of no use in data processing).
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] The specifications were presented to the executive committee on 4 September.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] They fell short of expectations: Joseph Wegstein noted that "it contains rough spots and requires some additions," and Bob Bemer later described them as a "hodgepodge." The committee was given until December to improve it.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] At a mid-September meeting, the committee discussed the new language's name.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Suggestions included "BUSY" (Business System), "INFOSYL" (Information System Language), and "COCOSYL" (Common Computer Systems Language).
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] It is unclear who coined the name "COBOL", although Bob Bemer later claimed it had been his suggestion.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] In October, the intermediate-range committee received copies of the FACT language specification created by Roy Nutt.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Its features impressed the committee so much that they passed a resolution to base COBOL on it.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] This was a blow to the short-range committee, who had made good progress on the specification.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Despite being technically superior, FACT had not been created with portability in mind or through manufacturer and user consensus.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] It also lacked a demonstrable implementation, allowing supporters of a FLOW-MATIC-based COBOL to overturn the resolution.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] RCA representative Howard Bromberg also blocked FACT, so that RCA's work on a COBOL implementation would not go to waste.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] It soon became apparent that the committee was too large to make any further progress quickly.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] A frustrated Howard Bromberg bought a $15 tombstone (in 1959; equivalent to roughly $170 now) with "COBOL" engraved on it and sent it to Charles Phillips to demonstrate his displeasure.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] The subcommittee did most of the work creating the specification, leaving the short-range committee to review and modify their work before producing the finished specification.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] The specifications were approved by the executive committee on 8 January 1960, and sent to the government printing office, which printed them as *COBOL 60*.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] The language's stated objectives were to allow efficient, portable programs to be easily written, to allow users to move to new systems with minimal effort and cost, and to be suitable for inexperienced programmers.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] The CODASYL Executive Committee later created the COBOL Maintenance Committee to answer questions from users and vendors and to improve and expand the specifications.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] During 1960, the list of manufacturers planning to build COBOL compilers grew.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] By September, five more manufacturers had joined CODASYL (Bendix, Control Data Corporation, General Electric (GE), National Cash Register, and Philco), and all represented manufacturers had announced COBOL compilers.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] GE and IBM planned to integrate COBOL into their own languages, GECOM and COMTRAN, respectively.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] In contrast, International Computers and Tabulators planned to replace their language, CODEL, with COBOL.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Meanwhile, RCA and Sperry Rand worked on creating COBOL compilers.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] The first COBOL program ran on 17 August on an RCA 501.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] On 6 and 7 December, the same COBOL program (albeit with minor changes) ran on an RCA computer and a Remington-Rand Univac computer, demonstrating that compatibility could be achieved.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Many logical flaws were found in *COBOL 60*, leading General Electric's Charles Katz to warn that it could not be interpreted unambiguously.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] A reluctant short-term committee performed a total cleanup, and, by March 1963, it was reported that COBOL's syntax was as definable as ALGOL's, although semantic ambiguities remained.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Early COBOL compilers were primitive and slow.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] A 1962 US Navy evaluation found compilation speeds of 3–11 statements per minute.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] By mid-1964, they had increased to 11–1000 statements per minute.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] It was observed that increasing memory would drastically increase speed and that compilation costs varied wildly: costs per statement were between $0.23 and $18.91.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] In late 1962, IBM announced that COBOL would be their primary development language and that development of COMTRAN would cease.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] The COBOL specification was revised three times in the five years after its publication.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] COBOL-60 was replaced in 1961 by COBOL-61.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] This was then replaced by the COBOL-61 Extended specifications in 1963, which introduced the sort and report writer facilities.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] The added facilities corrected flaws identified by Honeywell in late 1959 in a letter to the short-range committee.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] COBOL Edition 1965 brought further clarifications to the specifications and introduced facilities for handling mass storage files and tables.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Efforts began to standardize COBOL to overcome incompatibilities between versions.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] In late 1962, both ISO and the United States of America Standards Institute (now ANSI) formed groups to create standards.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] ANSI produced *USA Standard COBOL X3.23* in August 1968, which became the cornerstone for later versions.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] This version was known as American National Standard (ANS) COBOL and was adopted by ISO in 1972.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] By 1970, COBOL had become the most widely used programming language in the world.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Independently of the ANSI committee, the CODASYL Programming Language Committee was working on improving the language.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] They described new versions in 1968, 1969, 1970, and 1973, including changes such as new inter-program communication, debugging, and file merging facilities, as well as improved string handling and library inclusion features.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Although CODASYL was independent of the ANSI committee, the *CODASYL Journal of Development* was used by ANSI to identify features that were popular enough to warrant implementing.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] The Programming Language Committee also liaised with ECMA and the Japanese COBOL Standard committee.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] The Programming Language Committee was not well-known, however.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] The vice president, William Rinehuls, complained that two-thirds of the COBOL community did not know of the committee's existence.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] It also lacked the funds to make public documents, such as minutes of meetings and change proposals, freely available.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] In 1974, ANSI published a revised version of (ANS) COBOL, containing new features such as file organizations, the `DELETE` statement and the segmentation module.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Deleted features included the `NOTE` statement, the `EXAMINE` statement (which was replaced by `INSPECT`), and the implementer-defined random access module (which was superseded by the new sequential and relative I/O modules).
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] These made up 44 changes, which rendered existing statements incompatible with the new standard.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] The report writer was slated to be removed from COBOL but was reinstated before the standard was published.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] ISO later adopted the updated standard in 1978.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] In June 1978, work began on revising COBOL-74.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] The proposed standard (commonly called COBOL-80) differed significantly from the previous one, causing concerns about incompatibility and conversion costs.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Brophy, Senior Vice-president of Travelers Insurance, threatened to sue the standard committee because it was not upwards compatible with COBOL-74.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Brophy described previous conversions of their 40-million-line code base as "non-productive" and a "complete waste of our programmer resources".
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Later that year, the Data Processing Management Association (DPMA) said it was "strongly opposed" to the new standard, citing "prohibitive" conversion costs and enhancements that were "forced on the user".
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] During the first public review period, the committee received 2,200 responses, of which 1,700 were negative form letters.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Other responses were detailed analyses of the effect COBOL-80 would have on their systems; conversion costs were predicted to be at least 50 cents per line of code.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Fewer than a dozen of the responses were in favor of the proposed standard.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] ISO TC97-SC5 installed in 1979 the international COBOL Experts Group, on initiative of Wim Ebbinkhuijsen.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] The group consisted of COBOL experts from many countries, including the United States.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Its goal was to achieve mutual understanding and respect between ANSI and the rest of the world with regard to the need of new COBOL features.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] After three years, ISO changed the status of the group to a formal Working Group: WG 4 COBOL.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] The group took primary ownership and development of the COBOL standard, where ANSI made most of the proposals.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] In 1983, the DPMA withdrew its opposition to the standard, citing the responsiveness of the committee to public concerns.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] In the same year, a National Bureau of Standards study concluded that the proposed standard would present few problems.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] A year later, DEC released a VAX/VMS COBOL-80, and noted that conversion of COBOL-74 programs posed few problems.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] The new `EVALUATE` statement and inline `PERFORM` were particularly well received and improved productivity, thanks to simplified control flow and debugging.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] The second public review drew another 1,000 (mainly negative) responses, while the last drew just 25, by which time many concerns had been addressed.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] In 1985, the ISO Working Group 4 accepted the then-version of the ANSI proposed standard, made several changes and set it as the new ISO standard COBOL 85.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] The new standard was adopted by all national standard bodies, including ANSI.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Two amendments followed in 1989, and 1993.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] The first one introduced *Intrinsic function Module*, and the latter provided corrections.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] In 1997, Gartner Group estimated that there were a total of 200 billion lines of COBOL in existence, which ran 80% of all business programs.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] In the early 1990s, work began on adding object-oriented programming in the next full revision of COBOL.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Object-oriented features were taken from C++ and Smalltalk.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] The initial estimate was to have this revision completed by 1997, and an ISO Committee Draft (CD) was available by 1997.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Some vendors (including Micro Focus, Fujitsu, and IBM) introduced object-oriented syntax based on drafts of the full revision.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] The final approved ISO standard was approved and published in late 2002.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Fujitsu/GTSoftware, Micro Focus introduced object-oriented COBOL compilers targeting the .NET Framework.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] There were many other new features, many of which had been in the *CODASYL COBOL Journal of Development* since 1978 and had missed the opportunity to be included in COBOL-85.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Three corrigenda were published for the standard: two in 2006 and one in 2009.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Between 2003 and 2009, three Technical Reports (TRs) were produced describing object finalization, XML processing and collection classes for COBOL.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] COBOL 2002 suffered from poor support: no compilers completely supported the standard.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Micro Focus found that it was due to a lack of user demand for the new features and due to the abolition of the NIST test suite, which had been used to test compiler conformance.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] The standardization process was also found to be slow and under-resourced.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] `gcobol`, from GCC 15.1, is based on this standard.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] COBOL programs are used globally in governments and various industries including retail, travel, finance, and healthcare.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] COBOL currently runs on diverse operating systems such as z/OS, z/VSE, VME, Unix, NonStop OS, OpenVMS and Windows.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] In 1997, the Gartner Group reported that 80% of the world's business ran on COBOL with over 200 billion lines of code and 5 billion lines more being written annually.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] As of 2020, COBOL ran background processes 95% of the time a credit or debit card was swiped.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Near the end of the 20th century, the year 2000 problem (Y2K) was the focus of significant COBOL programming effort, sometimes by the same programmers who had designed the systems decades before.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] The particular level of effort required to correct COBOL code has been attributed to the large amount of business-oriented COBOL, as business applications use dates heavily, and to fixed-length data fields.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Some studies attribute as much as "24% of Y2K software repair costs to Cobol".
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] After the clean-up effort put into these programs for Y2K, a 2003 survey found that many remained in use.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] The authors said that the survey data suggest "a gradual decline in the importance of COBOL in application development over the [following] 10 years unless ... integration with other languages and technologies can be adopted".
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] In 2006 and 2012, *Computerworld* surveys (of 352 readers) found that over 60% of organizations used COBOL (more than C++ and Visual Basic .NET) and that for half of those, COBOL was used for the majority of their internal software.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] 36% of managers said they planned to migrate from COBOL, and 25% said that they would do so if not for the expense of rewriting legacy code.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Alternatively, some businesses have migrated their COBOL programs from mainframes to cheaper, faster hardware.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] By 2019, the number of COBOL programmers was shrinking fast due to retirements, leading to an impending skills gap in business and government organizations which still use mainframe systems for high-volume transaction processing.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Efforts to rewrite COBOL systems in newer languages have proven expensive and problematic, as has the outsourcing of code maintenance, thus proposals to train more people in COBOL are advocated.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Several banks have undertaken multi-year COBOL modernization efforts, sometimes resulting in widespread service disruptions that result in fines.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] During the COVID-19 pandemic and the ensuing surge of unemployment, several US states reported a shortage of skilled COBOL programmers to support the legacy systems used for unemployment benefit management.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Many of these systems had been in the process of conversion to more modern programming languages prior to the pandemic, but the process was put on hold.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] Similarly, the US Internal Revenue Service rushed to patch its COBOL-based Individual Master File in order to disburse the tens of millions of payments mandated by the Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p01] In 2024, the IRS announced a transition from COBOL to Java thanks to the Digital First Initiative.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] COBOL has an English-like syntax, which is used to describe nearly everything in COBOL programs.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] For example, a condition can be expressed as `x IS GREATER THAN y` or more concisely as `x GREATER y` or `x > y`.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] More complex conditions can be abbreviated by removing repeated conditions and variables.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] For example, `a > b AND a > c OR a = d` can be shortened to `a > b AND c OR = d`.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] To support this syntax, COBOL has over 300 keywords.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Some of the keywords are simple alternative or pluralized spellings of the same word, which provides for more grammatically appropriate statements and clauses; e.g., the `IN` and `OF` keywords can be used interchangeably, as can `TIME` and `TIMES`, and `VALUE` and `VALUES`.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Each COBOL program is made up of four basic lexical items: words, literals, picture character-strings and separators.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Words include reserved words and user-defined identifiers.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] They are up to 31 characters long and may include letters, digits, hyphens and underscores.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Separators include the space character and commas and semi-colons followed by a space.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] A COBOL program is split into four divisions: the identification division, the environment division, the data division and the procedure division.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] The identification division specifies the name and type of the source element and is where classes and interfaces are specified.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] The environment division specifies any program features that depend on the system running it, such as files and character sets.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] The data division is used to declare variables and parameters.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] The procedure division contains the program's statements.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Each division is sub-divided into sections, which are made up of paragraphs.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] COBOL's syntax is usually described with a unique metalanguage using braces, brackets, bars and underlining.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] The metalanguage was developed for the original COBOL specifications.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] The height of COBOL's popularity coincided with the era of keypunch machines and punched cards.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] The program itself was written onto punched cards, then read in and compiled, and the data fed into the program was sometimes on cards as well.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] COBOL can be written in two formats: fixed (the default) or free.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] In fixed-format, code must be aligned to fit in certain areas (a holdover from using punched cards).
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] In COBOL 2002, Areas A and B were merged to form the program-text area, which now ends at an implementor-defined column.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] COBOL 2002 also introduced free-format code.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Free-format code can be placed in any column of the file, as in newer programming languages.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Comments are specified using `*>`, which can be placed anywhere and can also be used in fixed-format source code.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Continuation lines are not present, and the `>>PAGE` directive replaces the `/` indicator.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] The identification division identifies the following code entity and contains the definition of a class or interface.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Classes and interfaces have been in COBOL since 2002.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Classes have factory objects, containing class methods and variables, and instance objects, containing instance methods and variables.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Inheritance and interfaces provide polymorphism.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Support for generic programming is provided through parameterized classes, which can be instantiated to use any class or interface.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Objects are stored as references which may be restricted to a certain type.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] There are two ways of calling a method: the `INVOKE` statement, which acts similarly to `CALL`, or through inline method invocation, which is analogous to using functions.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] COBOL does not provide a way to hide methods.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Class data can be hidden, however, by declaring it without a `PROPERTY` clause, which leaves external code no way to access it.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Method overloading was added in COBOL 2014.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] The environment division contains the configuration section and the input-output section.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] The configuration section is used to specify variable features such as currency signs, locales and character sets.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] The input-output section contains file-related information.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] COBOL supports three file formats, or **organizations**: sequential, indexed and relative.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] In sequential files, records are contiguous and must be traversed sequentially, similarly to a linked list.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Indexed files have one or more indexes which allow records to be randomly accessed and which can be sorted on them.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Each record must have a unique key, but other, **alternate**, record keys need not be unique.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Implementations of indexed files vary between vendors, although common implementations, such as C-ISAM and VSAM, are based on IBM's ISAM.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Other implementations are Record Management Services on OpenVMS and Enscribe on HPE NonStop (Tandem).
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Relative files, like indexed files, have a unique record key, but they do not have alternate keys.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] A relative record's key is its ordinal position; for example, the 10th record has a key of 10.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] This means that creating a record with a key of 5 may require the creation of (empty) preceding records.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Relative files also allow for both sequential and random access.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] A common non-standard extension is the **line sequential** organization, used to process text files.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Records in a file are terminated by a newline and may be of varying length.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Data items in COBOL are declared hierarchically through the use of level-numbers which indicate if a data item is part of another.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] An item with a higher level-number is subordinate to an item with a lower one.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Top-level data items, with a level-number of 1, are called **records**.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Items that have subordinate aggregate data are called **group items**; those that do not are called **elementary items**.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Level-numbers used to describe standard data items are between 1 and 49.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] In the above example, elementary item `num` and group item `the-date` are subordinate to the record `some-record`, while elementary items `the-year`, `the-month`, and `the-day` are part of the group item `the-date`.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Subordinate items can be disambiguated with the `IN` (or `OF`) keyword.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] The names `the-year`, `the-month`, and `the-day` are ambiguous by themselves, since more than one data item is defined with those names.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] To specify a particular data item, for instance one of the items contained within the `sale-date` group, the programmer would use `the-year IN sale-date` (or the equivalent `the-year OF sale-date`).
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] This syntax is similar to the "dot notation" supported by most contemporary languages.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] A level-number of 66 is used to declare a re-grouping of previously defined items, irrespective of how those items are structured.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] This data level, also referred to by the associated *`RENAMES` clause*, is rarely used and, circa 1988, was usually found in old programs.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Its ability to ignore the hierarchical and logical structure data meant its use was not recommended and many installations forbade its use.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] A 77 level-number indicates the item is stand-alone, and in such situations is equivalent to the level-number 01.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] An 88 level-number declares a **condition name** (a so-called 88-level) which is true when its parent data item contains one of the values specified in its `VALUE` clause.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] For example, the following code defines two 88-level condition-name items that are true or false depending on the current character data value of the `wage-type` data item.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] When the data item contains a value of `'H'`, the condition-name `wage-is-hourly` is true, whereas when it contains a value of `'S'` or `'Y'`, the condition-name `wage-is-yearly` is true.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] If the data item contains some other value, both of the condition-names are false.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Numeric data is converted between different representations and sizes silently and alphanumeric data can be placed in any data item that can be stored as a string, including numeric and group data.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] In contrast, object references and pointers may only be assigned from items of the same type and their values may be restricted to a certain type.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] A `PICTURE` (or `PIC`) clause is a string of characters, each of which represents a portion of the data item and what it may contain.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Some picture characters specify the type of the item and how many characters or digits it occupies in memory.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] For example, a `9` indicates a decimal digit, and an `S` indicates that the item is signed.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Other picture characters (called **insertion** and **editing** characters) specify how an item should be formatted.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Repeated characters can be specified more concisely by specifying a number in parentheses after a picture character; for example, `9(7)` is equivalent to `9999999`.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Picture specifications containing only digit (`9`) and sign (`S`) characters define purely **numeric** data items, while picture specifications containing alphabetic (`A`) or alphanumeric (`X`) characters define **alphanumeric** data items.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] The presence of other formatting characters define **edited numeric** or **edited alphanumeric** data items.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] The `USAGE` clause declares the format in which data is stored.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Depending on the data type, it can either complement or be used instead of a `PICTURE` clause.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] While it can be used to declare pointers and object references, it is mostly geared towards specifying numeric types.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] The report writer is a declarative facility for creating reports.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] The programmer need only specify the report layout and the data required to produce it, freeing them from having to write code to handle things like page breaks, data formatting, and headings and footings.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Reports are associated with report files, which are files which may only be written to through report writer statements.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Each report is defined in the report section of the data division.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] A report is split into report groups which define the report's headings, footings and details.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Reports work around hierarchical **control breaks**.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Control breaks occur when a key variable changes it value; for example, when creating a report detailing customers' orders, a control break could occur when the program reaches a different customer's orders.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Four statements control the report writer: `INITIATE`, which prepares the report writer for printing; `GENERATE`, which prints a report group; `SUPPRESS`, which suppresses the printing of a report group; and `TERMINATE`, which terminates report processing.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Use of the Report Writer facility tends to vary considerably; some organizations use it extensively and some not at all.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] In addition, implementations of Report Writer ranged in quality, with those at the lower end sometimes using excessive amounts of memory at runtime.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] The sections and paragraphs in the procedure division (collectively called procedures) can be used as labels and as simple subroutines.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Unlike in other divisions, paragraphs do not need to be in sections.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Execution goes down through the procedures of a program until it is terminated.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] To use procedures as subroutines, the `PERFORM` verb is used.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] A `PERFORM` statement somewhat resembles a procedure call in a newer languages in the sense that execution returns to the code following the `PERFORM` statement at the end of the called code; however, it does not provide a mechanism for parameter passing or for returning a result value.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] If a subroutine is invoked using a simple statement like `PERFORM subroutine`, then control returns at the end of the called procedure.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] However, `PERFORM` is unusual in that it may be used to call a range spanning a sequence of several adjacent procedures.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] The output of this program will be: "A A B C".
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] `PERFORM` also differs from conventional procedure calls in that there is, at least traditionally, no notion of a call stack.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] As a consequence, nested invocations are possible (a sequence of code being `PERFORM`'ed may execute a `PERFORM` statement itself), but require extra care if parts of the same code are executed by both invocations.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] The problem arises when the code in the inner invocation reaches the exit point of the outer invocation.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] More formally, if control passes through the exit point of a `PERFORM` invocation that was called earlier but has not yet completed, the COBOL 2002 standard stipulates that the behavior is undefined.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] The reason is that COBOL, rather than a "return address", operates with what may be called a continuation address.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] When control flow reaches the end of any procedure, the continuation address is looked up and control is transferred to that address.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Before the program runs, the continuation address for every procedure is initialized to the start address of the procedure that comes next in the program text so that, if no `PERFORM` statements happen, control flows from top to bottom through the program.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] But when a `PERFORM` statement executes, it modifies the continuation address of the called procedure (or the last procedure of the called range, if `PERFORM THRU` was used), so that control will return to the call site at the end.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] The original value is saved and is restored afterwards, but there is only one storage position.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] If two nested invocations operate on overlapping code, they may interfere which each other's management of the continuation address in several ways.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] One might expect that the output of this program would be "1 2 3 4 3": After displaying "2", the second `PERFORM` causes "3" and "4" to be displayed, and then the first invocation continues on with "3".
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] In traditional COBOL implementations, this is not the case.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Rather, the first `PERFORM` statement sets the continuation address at the end of `LABEL3` so that it will jump back to the call site inside `LABEL1`.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] The second `PERFORM` statement sets the return at the end of `LABEL4` but does not modify the continuation address of `LABEL3`, expecting it to be the default continuation.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Thus, when the inner invocation arrives at the end of `LABEL3`, it jumps back to the outer `PERFORM` statement, and the program stops having printed just "1 2 3".
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] On the other hand, in some COBOL implementations like the open-source TinyCOBOL compiler, the two `PERFORM` statements do not interfere with each other and the output is indeed "1 2 3 4 3".
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Therefore, the behavior in such cases is not only (perhaps) surprising, it is also not portable.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] A special consequence of this limitation is that `PERFORM` cannot be used to write recursive code, to write recursive routines, one must use a nested subprogram.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] One might expect that the output is "1 2 3 END END END", and in fact that is what some COBOL compilers will produce.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] But other compilers, like IBM COBOL, will produce code that prints "1 2 3 END END END END ..." and so on, printing "END" over and over in an endless loop.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Since there is limited space to store backup continuation addresses, the backups get overwritten in the course of recursive invocations, and all that can be restored is the jump back to `DISPLAY 'END'`.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] COBOL 2014 has 47 statements (also called **verbs**), which can be grouped into the following broad categories: control flow, I/O, data manipulation and the report writer.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] The report writer statements are covered in the report writer section.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] COBOL's conditional statements are `IF` and `EVALUATE`.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] `EVALUATE` is a switch-like statement with the added capability of evaluating multiple values and conditions.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] This can be used to implement decision tables.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] The `PERFORM` statement is used to define loops which are executed *until* a condition is true (not *while* true, which is more common in other languages).
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] It is also used to call procedures or ranges of procedures (see the procedures section for more details).
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] `CALL` and `INVOKE` call subprograms and methods, respectively.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] The name of the subprogram/method is contained in a string which may be a literal or a data item.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Parameters can be passed by reference, by content (where a copy is passed by reference) or by value (but only if a prototype is available).
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] `CANCEL` unloads subprograms from memory.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] `GO TO` causes the program to jump to a specified procedure.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] The `GOBACK` statement is a return statement and the `STOP` statement stops the program.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] The `EXIT` statement has six different formats: it can be used as a return statement, a break statement, a continue statement, an end marker or to leave a procedure.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Exceptions are raised by a `RAISE` statement and caught with a handler, or **declarative**, defined in the `DECLARATIVES` portion of the procedure division.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Declaratives are sections beginning with a `USE` statement which specify the errors to handle.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] `RESUME` is used in a declarative to jump to the statement after the one that raised the exception or to a procedure outside the `DECLARATIVES`.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Unlike other languages, uncaught exceptions may not terminate the program and the program can proceed unaffected.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] User interaction is done using `ACCEPT` and `DISPLAY`.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Files and tables are sorted using `SORT` and the `MERGE` verb merges and sorts files.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] The `RELEASE` verb provides records to sort and `RETURN` retrieves sorted records in order.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Some statements, such as `IF` and `READ`, may themselves contain statements.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Such statements may be terminated in two ways: by a period (**implicit termination**), which terminates *all* unterminated statements contained, or by a scope terminator, which terminates the nearest matching open statement.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Nested statements terminated with a period are a common source of bugs.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Here, the intent is to display `y` and `z` if condition `x` is true.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] However, `z` will be displayed whatever the value of `x` because the `IF` statement is terminated by an erroneous period after `DISPLAY y`.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Another bug is a result of the dangling else problem, when two `IF` statements can associate with an `ELSE`.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] In the above fragment, the `ELSE` associates with the `IF y` statement instead of the `IF x` statement, causing a bug.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Prior to the introduction of explicit scope terminators, preventing it would require `ELSE NEXT SENTENCE` to be placed after the inner `IF`.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] The original (1960) COBOL specification supported the infamous `ALTER X TO PROCEED TO Y` statement, for which many compilers generated self-modifying code.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] `X` and `Y` are procedure labels, and the single `GO TO` statement in procedure `X` executed after such an `ALTER` statement means `GO TO Y` instead.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] Many compilers still support it, but it was deemed obsolete in the COBOL 1985 standard and deleted in 2002.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] The `ALTER` statement was poorly regarded because it undermined "locality of context" and made a program's overall logic difficult to comprehend.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] When the now famous "Hello, World!" program example in *The C Programming Language* was first published in 1978 a similar mainframe COBOL program sample would have been submitted through JCL, very likely using a punch card reader, and 80 column punch cards.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] The listing below, *with an empty `DATA DIVISION`*, was tested using Linux and the System/370 Hercules emulator running MVS 3.8J.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] The JCL, written in July 2015, is derived from the Hercules tutorials and samples hosted by Jay Moseley.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] In keeping with COBOL programming of that era, HELLO, WORLD is displayed in all capital letters.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p02] The associated compiler listing generated over four pages of technical detail and job run information, for the single line of output from the 14 lines of COBOL.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] In the 1970s, adoption of the structured programming paradigm was becoming increasingly widespread.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] In a published dissent to Dijkstra's remarks, the computer scientist Howard E.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] Tompkins claimed that unstructured COBOL tended to be "written by programmers that have never had the benefit of structured COBOL taught well", arguing that the issue was primarily one of training.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] One cause of spaghetti code was the `GO TO` statement.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] Attempts to remove `GO TO`s from COBOL code, however, resulted in convoluted programs and reduced code quality.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] `GO TO`s were largely replaced by the `PERFORM` statement and procedures, which promoted modular programming and gave easy access to powerful looping facilities.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] However, `PERFORM` could be used only with procedures so loop bodies were not located where they were used, making programs harder to understand.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] Since the adoption of the 1985 standard, the need for `GO TO` has been completely obliviated by rich features of the `PERFORM` verb; however, `GO TO` remains for backwards compatibility, as it does in many other languages.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] COBOL programs were infamous for being monolithic and lacking modularization.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] COBOL code could be modularized only through procedures, which were found to be inadequate for large systems.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] Otherwise, it was required to `CALL` separately compiled programs for modularity.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] It was impossible to restrict access to data until the COBOL-85 standard, meaning a procedure could access and modify *any* data item.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] Furthermore, there was no way to pass parameters to a procedure, an omission Jean Sammet regarded as the committee's biggest mistake..
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] This problem was removed in the COBOL-85 standard with the introduction of the nested subprogram which allowed for modularity and locally isolated data items.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] Another complication stemmed from the ability to `PERFORM THRU` a specified sequence of procedures.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] This meant that control could jump to and return from any procedure, creating convoluted control flow and permitting a programmer to break the single-entry single-exit rule.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] This situation improved as COBOL adopted more features.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] COBOL-74 added subprograms, giving programmers the ability to control the data each part of the program could access.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] COBOL-85 then added nested subprograms, allowing programmers to hide subprograms.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] Further control over data and code came in 2002 when object-oriented programming, user-defined functions and user-defined data types were included.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] Nevertheless, much important legacy COBOL software uses unstructured code, which has become practically unmaintainable.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] It can be too risky and costly to modify even a simple section of code, since it may be used from unknown places in unknown ways.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] COBOL was intended to be a highly portable, "common" language.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] However, by 2001, around 300 dialects had been created.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] One source of dialects was the standard itself: the 1974 standard was composed of one mandatory nucleus and eleven functional modules, each containing two or three levels of support.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] This permitted 104,976 possible variants.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] COBOL-85 was not fully compatible with earlier versions, and its development was controversial.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] Brophy, the CIO of Travelers Insurance, spearheaded an effort to inform COBOL users of the heavy reprogramming costs of implementing the new standard.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] As a result, the ANSI COBOL Committee received more than 2,200 letters from the public, mostly negative, requiring the committee to make changes.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] On the other hand, conversion to COBOL-85 was thought to increase productivity in future years, thus justifying the conversion costs.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] COBOL syntax has often been criticized for its verbosity.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] Proponents say that this was intended to make the code self-documenting, easing program maintenance.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] COBOL was also intended to be easy for programmers to learn and use, while still being readable to non-technical staff such as managers.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] The desire for readability led to the use of English-like syntax and structural elements, such as nouns, verbs, clauses, sentences, sections, and divisions.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] Yet by 1984, maintainers of COBOL programs were struggling to deal with "incomprehensible" code and the main changes in COBOL-85 were there to help ease maintenance.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] Jean Sammet, a short-range committee member, noted that "little attempt was made to cater to the professional programmer, in fact people whose main interest is programming tend to be very unhappy with COBOL" which she attributed to COBOL's verbose syntax.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] Later, COBOL suffered from a shortage of material covering it; it took until 1963 for introductory books to appear (with Richard D.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] Irwin publishing a college textbook on COBOL in 1966).
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] Donald Nelson, chair of the CODASYL COBOL committee, said in 1984 that "academics ... hate COBOL" and that computer science graduates "had 'hate COBOL' drilled into them".
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] By the mid-1980s, there was also significant condescension towards COBOL in the business community from users of other languages, for example FORTRAN or assembler, implying that COBOL could be used only for non-challenging problems.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] In 2003, COBOL featured in 80% of information systems curricula in the United States, the same proportion as C++ and Java.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] Ten years later, a poll by Micro Focus found that 20% of university academics thought COBOL was outdated or dead and that 55% believed their students thought COBOL was outdated or dead.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] The same poll also found that only 25% of academics had COBOL programming on their curriculum even though 60% thought they should teach it.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] Doubts have been raised about the competence of the standards committee.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] COBOL standards have repeatedly suffered from delays: COBOL-85 arrived five years later than hoped, COBOL 2002 was five years late, and COBOL 2014 was six years late.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] To combat delays, the standard committee allowed the creation of optional addenda which would add features more quickly than by waiting for the next standard revision.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] However, some committee members raised concerns about incompatibilities between implementations and frequent modifications of the standard.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] COBOL's data structures influenced subsequent programming languages.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] Its record and file structure influenced PL/I and Pascal, and the `REDEFINES` clause was a predecessor to Pascal's variant records.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] Explicit file structure definitions preceded the development of database management systems and aggregated data was a significant advance over Fortran's arrays.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] `PICTURE` data declarations were incorporated into PL/I, with minor changes.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] COBOL's `COPY` facility, although considered "primitive", influenced the development of include directives.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] The focus on portability and standardization meant programs written in COBOL could be portable and facilitated the spread of the language to a wide variety of hardware platforms and operating systems.
[src:legacy-languages/cobol-p03] Additionally, the well-defined division structure restricts the definition of external references to the Environment Division, which simplifies platform changes in particular.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Forth typically combines a compiler with an integrated command shell, where the user interacts via subroutines called *words*.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Words can be defined, tested, redefined, and debugged without recompiling or restarting the whole program.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] All syntactic elements, including variables, operators, and control flow, are defined as words.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] A stack is used to pass parameters between words, leading to a Reverse Polish notation style.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] For much of Forth's existence, the standard technique was to compile to threaded code, which can be interpreted faster than bytecode.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] One of the early benefits of Forth was size: an entire development environment—including compiler, editor, and user programs—could fit in memory on an 8-bit or similarly limited system.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] No longer constrained by space, there are modern implementations that generate optimized machine code like other language compilers.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The relative simplicity of creating a basic Forth system has led to many personal and proprietary variants, such as the custom Forth used to implement the bestselling 1986 video game *Starflight* from Electronic Arts.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Forth is used in the Open Firmware boot loader, in spaceflight applications such as the *Philae* spacecraft, and in other embedded systems which involve interaction with hardware.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Beginning in the early 1980s, Moore developed a series of microprocessors for executing compiled Forth-like code directly and experimented with smaller languages based on Forth concepts, including cmForth and colorForth.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Most of these languages were created to support Moore's own projects, such as chip design.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Forth has a niche in astronomical and space applications as well as a history in embedded systems.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The Open Firmware boot ROMs used by Apple, IBM, Sun, and OLPC XO-1 contain a Forth environment.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Forth has often been used to bring up new hardware.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Forth was the first resident software on the new Intel 8086 chip in 1978, and MacFORTH was the first resident development system for the Macintosh 128K in 1984.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Circa 1982, Atari, Inc. used an elaborate, self-running demo written in Forth to showcase capabilities of the Atari 8-bit computers in department stores.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Electronic Arts published multiple video games in the 1980s that were written in Forth, including *Worms?* (1983), *Adventure Construction Set* (1984), *Amnesia* (1986), *Starflight* (1986), and *Lords of Conquest* (1986).
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Robot coding game *ChipWits* (1984) was developed in MacFORTH for the Macintosh 128K, while the Commodore 64 port was written with SuperForth 64.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The prototype of *Boulder Dash* (1984) was implemented in Forth before being rewritten in 6502 assembly language.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Ashton-Tate's RapidFile (1986), a flat-file database program, and VP-Planner from Paperback Software International (1983), a spreadsheet program competing with Lotus 1-2-3, were written in Forth.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The Canon Cat (1987) uses Forth for its system programming.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Rockwell produced single-chip microcomputers with resident Forth kernels: the R65F11 and R65F12.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] ASYST was a Forth expansion for measuring and controlling on PCs.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Moore's personal programming system, which had been in continuous development since 1968.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Forth was first exposed to other programmers in the early 1970s, starting with Elizabeth Rather at the United States National Radio Astronomy Observatory (NRAO).
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] After their work at NRAO, Charles Moore and Elizabeth Rather formed FORTH, Inc. in 1973, refining and porting Forth systems to dozens of other platforms in the next decade.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Moore saw Forth as a successor to compile-link-go third-generation programming languages, or software for "fourth generation" hardware.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] FORTH, Inc.'s microFORTH was developed for the Intel 8080, Motorola 6800, Zilog Z80, and RCA 1802 microprocessors, starting in 1976.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] MicroFORTH was later used by hobbyists to generate Forth systems for other architectures, such as the 6502 in 1978.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The Forth Interest Group was formed in 1978.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] It promoted and distributed its own version of the language, FIG-Forth, for most makes of home computer.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Forth was popular in the early 1980s, because it was well suited to the limited memory of microcomputers.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The ease of implementing the language led to many implementations.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The Jupiter ACE home computer has Forth in its ROM-resident operating system.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Insoft GraFORTH is a version of Forth with graphics extensions for the Apple II.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Common practice was codified in the de facto standards FORTH-79 and FORTH-83 in the years 1979 and 1983, respectively.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] These standards were unified by ANSI in 1994, commonly referred to as ANS Forth.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] As of 2018, the source for the original 1130 version of FORTH has been recovered, and is now being updated to run on a restored or emulated 1130 system.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Forth emphasizes the use of small, simple functions called *words*.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Words for bigger tasks call upon many smaller words that each accomplish a distinct sub-task.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] A large Forth program is a hierarchy of words.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] These words, being distinct modules that communicate implicitly via a stack mechanism, can be prototyped, built and tested independently.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The highest level of Forth code may resemble an English-language description of the application.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Forth has been called a *meta-application language*: a language that can be used to create problem-oriented languages.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Forth relies on implicit use of a data stack and reverse Polish notation which is commonly used in calculators from Hewlett-Packard.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] In RPN, the operator is placed after its operands, as opposed to the more common infix notation where the operator is placed between its operands.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Postfix notation makes the language easier to parse and extend; Forth's flexibility makes a static BNF grammar inappropriate, and it does not have a monolithic compiler.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Extending the compiler only requires writing a new word, instead of modifying a grammar and changing the underlying implementation.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] First the numbers 25 and 10 are put on the stack.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The word `*` takes the top two numbers from the stack, multiplies them, and puts the product back on the stack.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Then the number 50 is placed on the stack.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The word `+` takes the top two numbers from the stack, adds them, and puts the sum back on the stack.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] `CR` (carriage return) starts the output on a new line.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] As everything has completed successfully, the Forth system prints `OK`.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Even Forth's structural features are stack-based.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The colon indicates the beginning of a new definition, in this case a new word (again, *word* is the term used for a subroutine) called `FLOOR5`.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The text in parentheses is a comment, advising that this word expects a number on the stack and will return a possibly changed number (on the stack).
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] First a number (1 or 8) is pushed onto the stack, `FLOOR5` is called, which pops the number again and pushes the result.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] `CR` moves the output to a new line (again, this is only here for readability).
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Finally, a call to `.` pops the result and prints.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Forth's grammar has no official specification.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Instead, it is defined by a simple algorithm.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The interpreter reads a line of input from the user input device, which is then parsed for a word using spaces as a delimiter; some systems recognise additional whitespace characters.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] When the interpreter finds a word, it looks the word up in the *dictionary*.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] If the word is found, the interpreter executes the code associated with the word, and then returns to parse the rest of the input stream.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] If the word isn't found, the word is assumed to be a number and an attempt is made to convert it into a number and push it on the stack; if successful, the interpreter continues parsing the input stream.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Otherwise, if both the lookup and the number conversion fail, the interpreter prints the word followed by an error message indicating that the word is not recognised, flushes the input stream, and waits for new user input.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The definition of a new word is started with the word `:` (colon) and ends with the word `;` (semi-colon).
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] will compile the word `X`, and makes the name findable in the dictionary.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] When executed by typing `10 X` at the console this will print `11 10`.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Most Forth systems include an assembler to write words using the processor's facilities.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Forth assemblers often use a reverse Polish syntax in which the parameters of an instruction precede the instruction.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] A typical reverse Polish assembler prepares the operands on the stack and the mnemonic copies the whole instruction into memory as the last step.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] A Forth assembler is by nature a macro assembler, so that it is easy to define an alias for registers according to their role in the Forth system: e.g.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] "dsp" for the register used as the data stack pointer.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Most Forth systems run under a host operating system such as Microsoft Windows, Linux or a version of Unix and use the host operating system's file system for source and data files; the ANS Forth Standard describes the words used for I/O.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] All modern Forth systems use normal text files for source, even if they are embedded.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] An embedded system with a resident compiler gets its source via a serial line.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Classic Forth systems traditionally use neither operating system nor file system.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Instead of storing code in files, source code is stored in disk blocks written to physical disk addresses.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The word `BLOCK` is employed to translate the number of a 1K-sized block of disk space into the address of a buffer containing the data, which is managed automatically by the Forth system.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Block use has become rare since the mid-1990s.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] In a hosted system those blocks too are allocated in a normal file in any case.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Multitasking, most commonly cooperative round-robin scheduling, is normally available (although multitasking words and support are not covered by the ANS Forth Standard).
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The word `PAUSE` is used to save the current task's execution context, to locate the next task, and restore its execution context.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Each task has its own stacks, private copies of some control variables and a scratch area.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Swapping tasks is simple and efficient; as a result, Forth multitaskers are available even on very simple microcontrollers, such as the Intel 8051, Atmel AVR, and TI MSP430.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Other non-standard facilities include a mechanism for issuing calls to the host OS or windowing systems, and many provide extensions that employ the scheduling provided by the operating system.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Typically they have a larger and different set of words from the stand-alone Forth's `PAUSE` word for task creation, suspension, destruction and modification of priority.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] A full-featured Forth system with all source code will compile itself, a technique commonly called meta-compilation or self-hosting, by Forth programmers (although the term doesn't exactly match meta-compilation as it is normally defined).
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The usual method is to redefine the handful of words that place compiled bits into memory.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The compiler's words use specially named versions of fetch and store that can be redirected to a buffer area in memory.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The buffer area simulates or accesses a memory area beginning at a different address than the code buffer.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Such compilers define words to access both the target computer's memory, and the host (compiling) computer's memory.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] After the fetch and store operations are redefined for the code space, the compiler, assembler, etc. are recompiled using the new definitions of fetch and store.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] This effectively reuses all the code of the compiler and interpreter.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Then, the Forth system's code is compiled, but this version is stored in the buffer.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The buffer in memory is written to disk, and ways are provided to load it temporarily into memory for testing.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] When the new version appears to work, it is written over the previous version.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Numerous variations of such compilers exist for different environments.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] For embedded systems, the code may instead be written to another computer, a technique known as cross compilation, over a serial port or even a single TTL bit, while keeping the word names and other non-executing parts of the dictionary in the original compiling computer.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The minimum definitions for such a Forth compiler are the words that fetch and store a byte, and the word that commands a Forth word to be executed.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Often the most time-consuming part of writing a remote port is constructing the initial program to implement fetch, store and execute, but many modern microprocessors have integrated debugging features (such as the Motorola CPU32) that eliminate this task.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The basic data structure of Forth is the "dictionary" which maps "words" to executable code or named data structures.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The dictionary is laid out in memory as a tree of linked lists with the links proceeding from the latest (most recently) defined word to the oldest, until a sentinel value, usually a NULL pointer, is found.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] A context switch causes a list search to start at a different leaf.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] A linked list search continues as the branch merges into the main trunk leading eventually back to the sentinel, the root.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] In rare cases such as meta-compilation a dictionary might be isolated and stand-alone.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The effect resembles that of nesting namespaces and can overload keywords depending on the context.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] A defined word generally consists of *head* and *body* with the head consisting of the *name field* (NF) and the *link field* (LF), and body consisting of the *code field* (CF) and the *parameter field* (PF).
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Head and body of a dictionary entry are treated separately because they may not be contiguous.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] For example, when a Forth program is recompiled for a new platform, the head may remain on the compiling computer, while the body goes to the new platform.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] In some environments (such as embedded systems) the heads occupy memory unnecessarily.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] However, some cross-compilers may put heads in the target if the target itself is expected to support an interactive Forth.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The exact format of a dictionary entry is not prescribed, and implementations vary.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The compiler itself is not a monolithic program.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] It consists of Forth words visible to the system, and usable by a programmer.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] This allows a programmer to change the compiler's words for special purposes.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Compilation in traditional Forth systems is straightforward and does not involve building and optimizing an abstract representation of the code.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The "compile time" flag in the name field is set for words with "compile time" behavior.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Most simple words execute the same code whether they are typed on a command line, or embedded in code.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] When compiling these, the compiler simply places code or a threaded pointer to the word.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The classic examples of compile-time words are the control structures such as `IF` and `WHILE`.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Almost all of Forth's control structures and almost all of its compiler are implemented as compile-time words.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] For instance, `IF` and `WHILE`, and the words that match with those, set up `BRANCH` (unconditional branch) and `?BRANCH` (pop a value off the stack, and branch if it is false).
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Counted loop control flow words work similarly but set up combinations of primitive words that work with a counter, and so on.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] During compilation, the data stack is used to support control structure balancing, nesting, and back-patching of branch addresses.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The numbers after `BRANCH` represent relative jump addresses.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] `LIT` is the primitive word for pushing a "literal" number onto the data stack.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] (Faster, shorter code would be compiled using pointers to constants instead of `LIT` and embedded data, if any of the numbers involved have been separately defined as constants.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The word `:` (colon) parses a name as a parameter, creates a dictionary entry (a *colon definition*) and enters compilation state.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The interpreter continues to read space-delimited words from the user input device.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] If a word is found, the interpreter executes the *compilation semantics* associated with the word, instead of the *interpretation semantics*.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The default compilation semantics of a word are to append its interpretation semantics to the current definition.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The word `;` (semi-colon) finishes the current definition and returns to interpretation state.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] It is an example of a word whose compilation semantics differ from the default.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The interpretation semantics of `;` (semi-colon), most control flow words, and several other words are undefined in ANS Forth, meaning that they must only be used inside of definitions and not on the interactive command line.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The interpreter state can be changed manually with the words `[` (left-bracket) and `]` (right-bracket) which enter interpretation state or compilation state, respectively.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] These words can be used with the word `LITERAL` to calculate a value during a compilation and to insert the calculated value into the current colon definition.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] `LITERAL` has the compilation semantics to take an object from the data stack and to append semantics to the current colon definition to place that object on the data stack.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] In ANS Forth, the current state of the interpreter can be read from the flag `STATE` which contains the value true when in compilation state and false otherwise.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] This allows the implementation of so-called *state-smart words* with behavior that changes according to the current state of the interpreter.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The word `IMMEDIATE` marks the most recent colon definition as an *immediate word*, effectively replacing its compilation semantics with its interpretation semantics.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Immediate words are normally executed during compilation, not compiled, but this can be overridden by the programmer in either state.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] In ANS Forth, the word `POSTPONE` takes a name as a parameter and appends the compilation semantics of the named word to the current definition even if the word was marked immediate.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Forth-83 defined separate words `COMPILE` and `[COMPILE]` to force the compilation of non-immediate and immediate words, respectively.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Instead of reserving space for an Immediate flag in every definition, some implementations of Forth use an Immediates Dictionary which is checked first when in compile mode.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] In ANS Forth, unnamed words can be defined with the word `:NONAME` which compiles the following words up to the next `;` (semi-colon) and leaves an *execution token* on the data stack.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The execution token provides an opaque handle for the compiled semantics, similar to the function pointers of the C programming language.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Execution tokens can be stored in variables.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The word `EXECUTE` takes an execution token from the data stack and performs the associated semantics.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The word `COMPILE,` (compile-comma) takes an execution token from the data stack and appends the associated semantics to the current definition.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The word `'` (tick) takes the name of a word as a parameter and returns the execution token associated with that word on the data stack.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] In interpretation state, `' RANDOM-WORD EXECUTE` is equivalent to `RANDOM-WORD`.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The words `:` (colon), `POSTPONE`, `'` (tick) are examples of *parsing words* that take their arguments from the user input device instead of the data stack.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Another example is the word `(` (paren) which reads and ignores the following words up to and including the next right parenthesis and is used to place comments in a colon definition.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Similarly, the word `\` (backslash) is used for comments that continue to the end of the current line.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] To be parsed correctly, `(` (paren) and `\` (backslash) must be separated by whitespace from the following comment text.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] In most Forth systems, the body of a code definition consists of either machine language, or some form of threaded code.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The original Forth which follows the informal FIG standard (Forth Interest Group), is a TIL (Threaded Interpretive Language).
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] This is also called indirect-threaded code, but direct-threaded and subroutine threaded Forths have also become popular in modern times.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The fastest modern Forths, such as SwiftForth, VFX Forth, and iForth, compile Forth to native machine code.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] When a word is a variable or other data object, the CF points to the runtime code associated with the defining word that created it.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] A defining word has a characteristic "defining behavior" (creating a dictionary entry plus possibly allocating and initializing data space) and also specifies the behavior of an instance of the class of words constructed by this defining word.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Names an uninitialized, one-cell memory location.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Names a location; space may be allocated at this location, or it can be set to contain a string or other initialized value.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Instance behavior returns the address of the beginning of this space.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Forth also provides a facility by which a programmer can define new application-specific defining words, specifying both a custom defining behavior and instance behavior.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Some examples include circular buffers, named bits on an I/O port, and automatically indexed arrays.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Data objects defined by these and similar words are global in scope.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The function provided by local variables in other languages is provided by the data stack in Forth (although Forth also has real local variables).
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Forth programming style uses very few named data objects compared with other languages; typically such data objects are used to contain data which is used by a number of words or tasks (in a multitasked implementation).
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Forth does not enforce consistency of data type usage; it is the programmer's responsibility to use appropriate operators to fetch and store values or perform other operations on data.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The word `CR` (Carriage Return) causes the output following `CR` to be displayed on a new line.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The parsing word `."` (dot-quote) reads a double-quote delimited string and appends code to the current definition so that the parsed string will be displayed upon execution.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The space character separating the word `."` from the string `Hello, World!` is not included as part of the string.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] It is needed so that the parser recognizes `."` as a Forth word.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] `.(` (dot-paren) is an immediate word that parses a parenthesis-delimited string and displays it.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] As with the word `."` the space character separating `.(` from `Hello, World!` is not part of the string.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The word `CR` comes before the text to print.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] By convention, the Forth interpreter does not start output on a new line.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Also by convention, the interpreter waits for input at the end of the previous line, after an `ok` prompt.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] There is no implied "flush-buffer" action in Forth's `CR`, as sometimes is in other programming languages.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] This definition was written to use the ASCII value of the `Q` character (81) directly.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The text between the parentheses is a comment and is ignored by the compiler.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The word `EMIT` takes a value from the data stack and displays the corresponding character.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The parsing word `CHAR` takes a space-delimited word as parameter and places the value of its first character on the data stack.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The word `[CHAR]` is an immediate version of `CHAR`.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] This definition used `\` (backslash) for the describing comment.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Both `CHAR` and `[CHAR]` are predefined in ANS Forth.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] In 1987, Ron Rivest developed the RC4 cipher-system for RSA Data Security, Inc.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The following Standard Forth version uses Core and Core Extension words only.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] A processor designed to support a specific programming language is called a language "engine".
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Forth engines are hardware platforms specifically designed to support developing and running programs written in Forth.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] (Likewise, Lisp machines were specifically designed to support developing and running programs written in Lisp, the Pascal MicroEngine was specifically designed to support developing and running programs written in Pascal, etc.).
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] The first commercially available single-chip Forth engine was the Rockwell R65F11, a chip that includes a Forth kernel in ROM, an enhanced 6502, SRAM, and various interface circuits that previously required peripheral chips.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Many other commercial CPUs (Harris RTX-2000, Novix NC4016, F21, MARC4, KimKlone, etc.) and many homebrew CPUs (My4TH, J1, H2, Mark 1 FORTH Computer, etc.) are specifically designed to run Forth.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Typically they implement common Forth primitives such as the "Forth NEXT" as single instructions.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Because Forth is simple to implement and has no standard reference implementation, there are numerous versions of the language.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] In addition to supporting the standard varieties of desktop computer systems (POSIX, Microsoft Windows, macOS), many of these Forth systems also target a variety of embedded systems.
[src:legacy-languages/forth-programming-language] Listed here are some of the systems which conform to the 1994 ANS Forth standard.
[src:legacy-languages/fortran-p01] Fortran was originally developed by IBM with a reference manual being released in 1956; however, the first compilers only began to produce accurate code two years later.
[src:legacy-languages/fortran-p01] Fortran computer programs have been written to support scientific and engineering applications, such as numerical weather prediction, finite element analysis, computational fluid dynamics, plasma physics, geophysics, computational physics, crystallography and computational chemistry.
[src:legacy-languages/fortran-p01] It is a popular language for high-performance computing and is used for programs that benchmark and rank the world's fastest supercomputers.
[src:legacy-languages/fortran-p01] Fortran has evolved through numerous versions and dialects.
[src:legacy-languages/fortran-p01] The two most important early versions were FORTRAN II and FORTRAN IV.
[src:legacy-languages/fortran-p01] In 1966, the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) developed a standard for Fortran to limit proliferation of compilers using slightly different syntax.
[src:legacy-languages/fortran-p01] Successive versions have added support for a character data type, structured programming (Fortran 77), array programming, modular programming, generic programming (Fortran 90), parallel computing (Fortran 95), object-oriented programming (Fortran 2003), and concurrent programming (Fortran 2008).
[src:legacy-languages/fortran-p01] The first manual for FORTRAN describes it as a *Formula Translating System*, and printed the name with small caps, Fortran.
[src:legacy-languages/fortran-p01] Other sources suggest the name stands for *Formula Translator*, or, most commonly, *Formula Translation*.
[src:legacy-languages/fortran-p01] Early IBM computers did not support lowercase letters, and the names of versions of the language through FORTRAN 77 were usually spelled in all-uppercase.
[src:legacy-languages/fortran-p01] FORTRAN 77 was the last version in which the Fortran character set included only uppercase letters.
[src:legacy-languages/fortran-p01] The Fortran 90 standard changed the language name from "FORTRAN" with all-caps to "Fortran" with initial caps.
[src:legacy-languages/fortran-p01] Backus submitted a proposal to his superiors at IBM to develop a more practical alternative to assembly language for programming their IBM 704 mainframe computer.
[src:legacy-languages/fortran-p01] Backus' historic FORTRAN team consisted of programmers Richard Goldberg, Sheldon F.
[src:legacy-languages/fortran-p01] Best, Harlan Herrick, Peter Sheridan, Roy Nutt, Robert Nelson, Irving Ziller, Harold Stern, Lois Haibt, and David Sayre.
